1
00:00:02,000 --> 00:00:07,000
Fm Movie

2
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:13,000
Fm Movie
3
00:00:11,178 --> 00:00:13,180
[overlapping chatter]

4
00:00:30,114 --> 00:00:31,741
[crew chattering]

5
00:00:39,415 --> 00:00:41,125
-Gotta get close to you, buddy.
-There you go.

6
00:00:41,208 --> 00:00:42,710
-Took about two minutes.
-We good. We good.

7
00:00:44,712 --> 00:00:47,757
Hi. You probably recognize me,
but a few years ago,

8
00:00:47,840 --> 00:00:49,800
I was sitting where you are today.

9
00:00:49,884 --> 00:00:51,761
Hardly anyone knew who Michael Jordan was.

10
00:00:51,844 --> 00:00:53,137
[chattering]

11
00:00:58,309 --> 00:01:01,896
The All American Game is a chance
to compete on national television,

12
00:01:01,979 --> 00:01:04,774
and to play with the best high school
basketball talent in the world.

13
00:01:05,775 --> 00:01:09,153
The competition is tough this week,
and it gets even tougher.

14
00:01:09,236 --> 00:01:10,821
Let's go. Hey, East on three.

15
00:01:10,905 --> 00:01:11,989
-One, two, three.
-[all] East!

16
00:01:12,072 --> 00:01:15,367
[announcer] …California. Number 10.
Amari Bailey!

17
00:01:15,451 --> 00:01:17,119
So, make the most of it.

18
00:01:17,203 --> 00:01:20,873
But just remember,
when you get to the NBA, the fun's over.

19
00:01:20,956 --> 00:01:22,291
'Cause I'll be waiting for you.

20
00:01:25,419 --> 00:01:30,883
LeBron James. At the St. Vincent-St. Mary.
National champs once again.

21
00:01:30,966 --> 00:01:32,176
I keep telling everybody.

22
00:01:32,259 --> 00:01:33,803
Number one in the country.

23
00:01:33,886 --> 00:01:36,222
[stammers] I'm up here chillin'.
What's up, bruh?

24
00:01:36,305 --> 00:01:40,726
You didn't get where you are today
without hours and hours of work,

25
00:01:40,810 --> 00:01:43,521
with a ball, and a dream, and a body.

26
00:01:44,604 --> 00:01:46,732
[Rose] For a basketball player,

27
00:01:47,316 --> 00:01:49,902
playing at the McDonald's
high school All American Game

28
00:01:49,985 --> 00:01:53,447
is the equivalent of going to the Oscars.

29
00:01:53,989 --> 00:01:55,199
That's the holy grail.

30
00:01:55,282 --> 00:01:58,077
When you get that invite
to play in that game,

31
00:01:58,160 --> 00:02:01,705
you tell yourself the first thing,
"I'm going to the league."

32
00:02:01,789 --> 00:02:03,916
I think the big thing,
you got a guy like Bob Geoghan,

33
00:02:03,999 --> 00:02:05,417
who puts in a lot of time with this.

34
00:02:05,501 --> 00:02:07,670
And that's the kind of thing
that makes this successful.

35
00:02:07,753 --> 00:02:11,799
Thirty NBA teams, over 100 NBA scouts
in South Bend this week.

36
00:02:11,882 --> 00:02:13,551
How does that affect your game?

37
00:02:13,634 --> 00:02:15,636
It really doesn't. You know,
I just gotta come out and play hard.

38
00:02:15,719 --> 00:02:18,013
I really can't… I can't get caught up
in the names that's here.

39
00:02:18,097 --> 00:02:20,057
You know, the Pat Rileys
and the Larry Birds and those guys.

40
00:02:20,140 --> 00:02:23,394
I just gotta come out, play hard,
represent myself, represent my community.

41
00:02:23,477 --> 00:02:26,939
Oh, yeah, it's everything and much more.
Um, just being here, being on national TV,

42
00:02:27,022 --> 00:02:28,983
being able to play
with all these great players.

43
00:02:29,066 --> 00:02:30,860
Uh, it's just a wonderful dream come true.

44
00:02:30,943 --> 00:02:32,486
Some day we'll have
a girl's dunk contest, right?

45
00:02:32,570 --> 00:02:34,864
Of course. 'Cause girls can do anything
that boys can do. [chuckles]

46
00:02:34,947 --> 00:02:36,115
[reporter chuckles] All right. Greg.

47
00:02:36,198 --> 00:02:39,451
I'm glad I played in the game.
Uh, and I'm glad we got the win.

48
00:02:40,077 --> 00:02:43,454
Everybody see the basketball game tonight,
but, you know, it's a lot more than that.

49
00:03:15,446 --> 00:03:18,324
[automated voice] McDonald's All American
High School Basketball Game.

50
00:03:53,025 --> 00:03:54,442
[chattering]

51
00:03:57,863 --> 00:04:01,116
McDonald's All American.
Glad to be here is all I can say.

52
00:04:06,080 --> 00:04:07,164
-Toast to McDonald's.
-Yo!

53
00:04:07,247 --> 00:04:08,290
You're 'bout to spill it.

54
00:04:08,374 --> 00:04:09,708
[mutters indistinctly]

55
00:04:11,085 --> 00:04:12,503
That's why I'm like, "Real life TV."

56
00:04:12,586 --> 00:04:14,880
Yeah, I was, like, this is not just,
like, a workout. This is like--

57
00:04:14,964 --> 00:04:16,714
Right. I mean,
if you're doing a scrimmage maybe.

58
00:04:16,798 --> 00:04:18,466
-No, yeah. There you go.
-Like, just practice.

59
00:04:20,886 --> 00:04:23,514
She's the number one player
in the country. I want her spot.

60
00:04:23,597 --> 00:04:25,808
But it's cool.
It's all love, regardless. Period.

61
00:04:27,726 --> 00:04:29,395
This really is my one way out.

62
00:04:31,021 --> 00:04:32,314
Without basketball, I wouldn't be me.

63
00:04:32,398 --> 00:04:34,650
Without basketball,
I wouldn't be where I am right now.

64
00:04:38,320 --> 00:04:41,824
Everybody always dreams about becoming
a McDonald's All American.

65
00:04:41,907 --> 00:04:43,450
And, well, I know each and every one of us

66
00:04:43,534 --> 00:04:46,161
is fortunate
and really grateful to be here.

67
00:04:46,245 --> 00:04:49,957
We've all put in endless hours,
endless time, and endless dedication

68
00:04:50,040 --> 00:04:53,127
just to try to get better and try to be
the best basketball player we can.

69
00:04:56,088 --> 00:04:58,507
This the best of the best.
Like, it don't get much better than this.

70
00:04:58,590 --> 00:05:01,927
And I like to compete against the best,
like, just to see where I'm at.

71
00:05:03,012 --> 00:05:05,597
Because I feel like if you can
beat the best, then you the best.

72
00:05:07,683 --> 00:05:09,768
Everyone get the same treatment,
for real, for real.

73
00:05:09,852 --> 00:05:12,229
Just go out there, compete, play hard.

74
00:05:14,857 --> 00:05:18,277
It means the world to me
to be one of the 48 All Americans.

75
00:05:18,360 --> 00:05:20,070
I mean, it's history.

76
00:05:22,448 --> 00:05:25,659
There's never as much talent
on the floor at the same time.

77
00:05:25,743 --> 00:05:28,537
You're the best of the best.
You're the elite.

78
00:05:28,620 --> 00:05:31,707
That being said, this is the reset button.

79
00:05:31,790 --> 00:05:34,960
The evaluation process
starts all over again.

80
00:05:35,044 --> 00:05:39,048
How hard you go, your IQ.
So, they're evaluating everything.

81
00:05:39,798 --> 00:05:42,134
I've talked to almost
every NBA GM, scouts,

82
00:05:42,718 --> 00:05:46,013
and they'll say the number one event
to evaluate kids pre-draft

83
00:05:46,096 --> 00:05:47,514
is the McDonald's All American Games.

84
00:05:47,598 --> 00:05:51,560
Because never is there 24 great players
on the same courts.

85
00:05:51,643 --> 00:05:53,479
As a basketball guy,
there's nothing better than that.

86
00:05:56,815 --> 00:05:59,943
[Hill] When you're a kid
and you're dreaming about, like,

87
00:06:00,027 --> 00:06:03,697
"Man, like, what do I wanna do
when I'm, you know, throughout my career?"

88
00:06:05,866 --> 00:06:09,661
Playing in a McDonald's game,
that's one of those milestones.

89
00:06:09,745 --> 00:06:11,914
It's one of those accomplishments
that you hope,

90
00:06:11,997 --> 00:06:15,876
that when you look back,
you're fortunate enough to achieve.

91
00:06:15,959 --> 00:06:18,212
It certainly sparks some great memories.

92
00:06:18,837 --> 00:06:20,422
And certainly appreciative of them.

93
00:06:25,219 --> 00:06:27,262
-Hello, everybody.
-[team] Hello!

94
00:06:27,346 --> 00:06:29,640
I'm Sonny. I don't know all your names,

95
00:06:29,723 --> 00:06:32,558
but we're gonna have
a good conversation here.

96
00:06:32,643 --> 00:06:35,521
Listen, pay attention, and do
whatever you want with it when it's over.

97
00:06:35,604 --> 00:06:37,773
-[team chuckling]
-That's all I can ask.

98
00:06:38,398 --> 00:06:42,027
Your documentary
will be a true documentary.

99
00:06:42,111 --> 00:06:44,655
It's-It's a good story. It really is.

100
00:06:44,738 --> 00:06:51,370
It opened the doors for thousands
and thousands of young people in America.

101
00:06:53,163 --> 00:06:57,543
"Sonny, I met you for the first time
in 1973

102
00:06:57,626 --> 00:07:02,631
when you came to DC to discuss my creating
the McDonald's Capital Classic."

103
00:07:03,507 --> 00:07:09,888
Bob Geoghan was one of the few
sports promoters in the Washington DC area

104
00:07:09,972 --> 00:07:12,766
that never made money. [chuckles]

105
00:07:13,809 --> 00:07:16,645
But he had a passion for basketball.

106
00:07:16,728 --> 00:07:20,023
[Joe] He'd say, you know, the goal is,
you gotta get the guy off the barstool.

107
00:07:20,107 --> 00:07:23,402
Just the local, 20, 30-year-old
that just wants to come to a game.

108
00:07:23,485 --> 00:07:25,195
We gotta get them to come to the game.

109
00:07:25,779 --> 00:07:27,072
[narrator] Before the 1960s,

110
00:07:27,156 --> 00:07:30,826
high school basketball players
had no platform to compete nationally,

111
00:07:30,909 --> 00:07:34,705
and recognition came primarily through
newspapers and magazines.

112
00:07:35,247 --> 00:07:36,832
Sonny Vaccaro saw this gap,

113
00:07:36,915 --> 00:07:40,627
and created a regional high school
all-star game, called "The Dapper Dan."

114
00:07:41,503 --> 00:07:43,422
Inspired by Sonny's initiative,

115
00:07:43,505 --> 00:07:46,258
Bob Geoghan had an idea
to make a national game,

116
00:07:46,341 --> 00:07:48,802
so fans could see the best
high school players in the country

117
00:07:48,886 --> 00:07:50,345
compete against each other.

118
00:07:51,013 --> 00:07:54,558
Geoghan approached Bob Beavers
from McDonald's, and Morgan Wootten,

119
00:07:54,641 --> 00:07:58,478
who then recruited basketball leaders
like Sonny Hill, Howard Garfinkel,

120
00:07:58,562 --> 00:08:01,565
and the great John Wooden
to ensure the game's success.

121
00:08:01,648 --> 00:08:04,067
Initially, Wooden was against
all-star games,

122
00:08:04,151 --> 00:08:06,278
but Morgan convinced him
to support the event

123
00:08:06,361 --> 00:08:09,573
because it was tied to charity
and the Ronald McDonald house.

124
00:08:09,656 --> 00:08:11,074
Wooden eventually agreed,

125
00:08:11,158 --> 00:08:13,452
and the McDonald's All American Game
was born.

126
00:08:16,038 --> 00:08:17,456
I need to take a drink.

127
00:08:18,624 --> 00:08:21,668
After you went through all that trouble
getting me this, let me take a drink.

128
00:08:24,796 --> 00:08:26,089
[exhales sharply] Okay.

129
00:08:26,173 --> 00:08:29,760
I kinda was just one of these people
who had a vision

130
00:08:29,843 --> 00:08:32,929
and just kinda worked to see
if I could make it really happen.

131
00:08:33,013 --> 00:08:35,599
And so, I went
to the McDonald's Corporation,

132
00:08:35,682 --> 00:08:39,269
and I asked them if they would
underwrite the game, and they…

133
00:08:39,352 --> 00:08:41,813
and I thought they were a big corporation
and they could run the game,

134
00:08:41,897 --> 00:08:43,690
I was just gonna buy a ticket
and watch it.

135
00:08:43,774 --> 00:08:46,151
And they said, "Well, we're great
at marketing hamburgers,

136
00:08:46,235 --> 00:08:48,695
we know nothing about running
high school all-star games.

137
00:08:48,779 --> 00:08:52,324
And since you have the three years'
experience, you're gonna have to do it."

138
00:08:58,789 --> 00:09:03,585
And you have over a 60% chance
of having a significant NBA or WNBA career

139
00:09:03,669 --> 00:09:05,128
if you're a McDonald's All American.

140
00:09:05,212 --> 00:09:08,966
So, these are the best players
at-at their age in the world.

141
00:09:09,049 --> 00:09:11,134
On the selection committee today,

142
00:09:11,218 --> 00:09:14,972
there's 21 voting members,
and then 23 with Joe and I.

143
00:09:15,055 --> 00:09:17,557
They work hard. They work countless hours.

144
00:09:17,641 --> 00:09:20,769
Uh, they're in every high school gym
during the high school season,

145
00:09:20,852 --> 00:09:22,479
they're on the road all summer at camps.

146
00:09:22,562 --> 00:09:25,148
Not only are we looking for
the best basketball player,

147
00:09:25,232 --> 00:09:28,151
we're looking for pretty well-rounded
and good person.

148
00:09:28,235 --> 00:09:32,030
What's their impact gonna be in college,
in the NBA, the WNBA?

149
00:09:32,114 --> 00:09:34,866
Where is their future going,
and their potential?

150
00:09:34,950 --> 00:09:37,744
[leader] Welcome,
welcome to the greatest city on Earth.

151
00:09:42,708 --> 00:09:47,504
Congratulations on being selected
as, uh, McDonald's All Americans.

152
00:09:47,587 --> 00:09:50,757
I know right now you kinda not able
to appreciate the moment,

153
00:09:50,841 --> 00:09:54,553
but you doing some, like, really dope
and amazing stuff right now. Like…

154
00:09:54,636 --> 00:09:59,516
As a historian, I-I really, really
appreciate, uh, history being made.

155
00:09:59,599 --> 00:10:01,685
And right now, you guys
are literally making history.

156
00:10:01,768 --> 00:10:04,896
Whether you live to be 95 or 105,

157
00:10:04,980 --> 00:10:08,317
like, your name is going
in the history book right now.

158
00:10:08,400 --> 00:10:10,110
You are cemented forever.

159
00:10:13,780 --> 00:10:18,327
It's such a surreal feeling being able
to put on that McDonald's uniform.

160
00:10:18,410 --> 00:10:22,122
I… I would have dreams
of just being here, honestly. Um…

161
00:10:22,205 --> 00:10:23,582
Words can't really describe it.

162
00:10:23,665 --> 00:10:25,417
I feel like
there's a little bit more respect

163
00:10:25,500 --> 00:10:28,462
that you can put on everyone's name
that's a McDonald's All American now.

164
00:10:29,588 --> 00:10:34,176
I think I was at school. I was in class,
and my mom texted me,

165
00:10:34,259 --> 00:10:35,677
"Please step out of the class,
I have to call you."

166
00:10:35,761 --> 00:10:37,512
So, I'm thinking
something bad's happening,

167
00:10:37,596 --> 00:10:41,641
but whenever she called me
she said, "I'm so proud of you.

168
00:10:41,725 --> 00:10:43,310
You're a McDonald's All American."

169
00:10:45,645 --> 00:10:48,231
I was at practice and my coach told me,
she was like,

170
00:10:48,315 --> 00:10:50,400
"You know, Janiah, you made it."
I was like…

171
00:10:50,484 --> 00:10:51,943
People like,
"Do you think you're gonna make it?"

172
00:10:52,027 --> 00:10:53,362
I was like, "I don't know,
I really hope so."

173
00:10:53,445 --> 00:10:56,323
They're like, "You know you're gonna
make it." I'm like, "I really don't know."

174
00:10:56,406 --> 00:10:58,492
You never know how people thinking,
how the committee's thinking,

175
00:10:58,575 --> 00:11:01,203
but when I made it, it was…
it was actually crazy.

176
00:11:01,286 --> 00:11:02,996
[stutters] I started crying.

177
00:11:03,080 --> 00:11:05,916
My teammates came around me.
They-They hugged me.

178
00:11:05,999 --> 00:11:08,377
They let me know they were proud of me,
and that I deserved it.

179
00:11:08,460 --> 00:11:09,920
[speaks indistinctly]

180
00:11:10,003 --> 00:11:11,046
[chuckling]

181
00:11:11,129 --> 00:11:13,382
I was at my high school.
We did, like, a little watch party, right?

182
00:11:13,465 --> 00:11:16,468
And my coach is like, "Yeah, we gonna go
buy a whole bunch of McDonald's,

183
00:11:16,551 --> 00:11:18,637
we finna get the drinks.
This-The ice cream, all that."

184
00:11:18,720 --> 00:11:20,889
I'm like, "Coach, bruh."
I was nervous. I'm like, "Bruh,

185
00:11:20,972 --> 00:11:23,683
if I don't get it, you know
how embarrassing that's gonna be, bruh?"

186
00:11:23,767 --> 00:11:26,937
So, we had this big ol' watch party.
We watching ESPN, man.

187
00:11:27,020 --> 00:11:29,064
Oh, you gotta turn this up.
Where's the speaker at?

188
00:11:29,940 --> 00:11:31,900
They on TV, they talking 'bout
McDonald, McDonald.

189
00:11:31,983 --> 00:11:34,277
And then, it comes to time,
they like, "Now, the girls."

190
00:11:34,361 --> 00:11:36,863
-[teammate whimpers]
-[boy] Oh, it's right now. Okay, okay!

191
00:11:36,947 --> 00:11:39,533
Hold up, y'all. Hold up, y'all.
Y'all gotta be quiet.

192
00:11:39,616 --> 00:11:40,700
Y'all gotta be quiet.

193
00:11:41,284 --> 00:11:42,327
And then…

194
00:11:42,411 --> 00:11:45,997
…it's Kiki Rice, Janiah Barker,
and Ayanna Patterson.

195
00:11:46,081 --> 00:11:48,917
And then, we also have Paris Clark,
Flau'jae Johnson…

196
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:51,253
-Oh, my… [screams]
-[all yelling and cheering]

197
00:11:53,839 --> 00:11:57,175
My hard work finally paying off.
Like, they finally seein' me.

198
00:11:58,468 --> 00:11:59,678
They seein' what I knew.

199
00:12:00,345 --> 00:12:02,889
Uh, they validating it for me.
They stampin' it for me.

200
00:12:05,475 --> 00:12:09,604
I'm so proud of you. I'm so proud of you.
Oh, congratulations.

201
00:12:09,688 --> 00:12:13,024
[sobbing] Oh, my God! Oh, my God!

202
00:12:13,108 --> 00:12:18,530
Oh, my God! Go look at Twitter, bro.
I'm a McDonald All American!

203
00:12:18,613 --> 00:12:19,865
Oh, my God!

204
00:12:21,741 --> 00:12:25,078
I'm a McDonald All American, bro!
[chuckles]

205
00:12:26,246 --> 00:12:29,249
I'm a McDonald All American!

206
00:12:30,959 --> 00:12:33,503
That was probably, like, the best moment
of my life, for real, for real.

207
00:12:36,631 --> 00:12:37,757
[chuckles]

208
00:12:37,841 --> 00:12:41,845
The game touches virtually
every high school senior in the country

209
00:12:41,928 --> 00:12:43,346
who's a basketball player.

210
00:12:43,430 --> 00:12:45,515
I wanted every kid in America

211
00:12:45,599 --> 00:12:48,477
to grow up dreaming of being
a McDonald's All American.

212
00:12:49,352 --> 00:12:52,230
You know, when you're little,
you see the All American games on TV,

213
00:12:52,314 --> 00:12:55,233
you see all the stars that have came
before you, and it's just, you know,

214
00:12:55,317 --> 00:12:57,486
the greatest experience
to actually be here and soak it all up.

215
00:12:57,569 --> 00:12:59,696
My dad got a phone call,
and they was like,

216
00:12:59,779 --> 00:13:01,990
"Yeah, you know, this is such and such,

217
00:13:02,073 --> 00:13:05,660
and your son made the McDonald's
All American team." And I was just in awe.

218
00:13:05,744 --> 00:13:09,331
Being a McDonald's All American
is such an honor, and um,

219
00:13:09,414 --> 00:13:12,626
it's above every accomplishment
that I've had throughout my career.

220
00:13:12,709 --> 00:13:15,962
I mean, I had a chance to visit
the Ronald McDonald House today.

221
00:13:16,046 --> 00:13:18,173
It was a great sight, you know,
just playing with the kids, having fun.

222
00:13:18,256 --> 00:13:19,883
Actually going
to the Ronald McDonald House

223
00:13:19,966 --> 00:13:22,969
and seeing the families and how they live,
and being able to, you know,

224
00:13:23,053 --> 00:13:25,388
put a smile on their face.
It's just a great feeling.

225
00:13:25,472 --> 00:13:29,226
Uh, feels great knowing
that Michael Jordan,

226
00:13:29,309 --> 00:13:32,812
uh, there's so many names that…
I could go on and on.

227
00:13:32,896 --> 00:13:36,650
That means it's… it's so many kids and
so many basketball players around here,

228
00:13:36,733 --> 00:13:39,986
that you being picked out of 24 people,
out of all them people.

229
00:13:40,070 --> 00:13:41,780
And it is a great honor to get there.

230
00:13:41,863 --> 00:13:44,699
Well, Mike, I think it's gonna be
a tremendous game, and without a doubt,

231
00:13:44,783 --> 00:13:46,868
this is the game that has probably
generated more interest

232
00:13:46,952 --> 00:13:49,162
than any other game in the last decade.

233
00:13:49,246 --> 00:13:50,747
I think the reason why is…

234
00:13:50,830 --> 00:13:53,542
the fella out there on the court,
number 32, Earvin "Magic" Johnson.

235
00:13:53,625 --> 00:13:56,962
Everybody's first team all-state player,
and first team All American.

236
00:13:57,045 --> 00:13:58,129
[Joe] My dad, at the time,

237
00:13:58,213 --> 00:14:00,799
was calling college coaches and saying,
"Do we have the right guys?"

238
00:14:00,882 --> 00:14:02,551
He called Johnny Orr, and he said,

239
00:14:03,134 --> 00:14:05,720
"Morgan, we got this kid up in Michigan
named Earvin."

240
00:14:05,804 --> 00:14:09,057
The last player picked was Magic Johnson.

241
00:14:11,059 --> 00:14:13,645
[Silver] Magic, at that time,
is a senior in high school.

242
00:14:13,728 --> 00:14:17,274
His personality
is what you see him today to be.

243
00:14:17,357 --> 00:14:18,733
He was totally out there.

244
00:14:18,817 --> 00:14:20,610
[reporter] Earvin Johnson,
if you have not heard the name.

245
00:14:20,694 --> 00:14:22,737
[commentator] Johnson's got it.

246
00:14:22,821 --> 00:14:26,241
Johnson will drive, he'll stop,
he'll shoot and score.

247
00:14:26,324 --> 00:14:29,327
[Ernie Johnson] Earvin Johnson
has always been something special,

248
00:14:29,411 --> 00:14:32,497
even before we came to know him
simply as Magic.

249
00:14:32,581 --> 00:14:36,793
[Rose] The game-changing
6'9" point guard with the infectious smile

250
00:14:36,876 --> 00:14:40,547
that became a springboard
to bridging high school

251
00:14:40,630 --> 00:14:42,841
'cause he was in an All American,

252
00:14:42,924 --> 00:14:46,219
college, because he was a champion,
and then the NBA,

253
00:14:46,303 --> 00:14:48,471
he came in right away being the champion.

254
00:14:48,555 --> 00:14:51,057
And the reason to this day
I'm still rocking the goatee.

255
00:14:52,434 --> 00:14:54,060
[Dominique Wilkins]
You heard about Magic Johnson.

256
00:14:54,144 --> 00:14:56,396
When you talk about the ambassador

257
00:14:56,479 --> 00:14:58,648
at that time for the McDonald's game,
he was the guy.

258
00:14:59,566 --> 00:15:02,319
We wanted to be where Magic Johnson was,
you know.

259
00:15:02,402 --> 00:15:04,154
We wanted to make that McDonald's team.

260
00:15:04,237 --> 00:15:06,281
It's been an honor and a privilege for me

261
00:15:06,364 --> 00:15:09,326
from where I came from
and my athletic ability

262
00:15:09,409 --> 00:15:12,203
to be meeting
some of the greats of the game.

263
00:15:12,287 --> 00:15:16,166
Not only great athletes,
but great coaches and great people.

264
00:15:16,249 --> 00:15:21,671
I can't think of a more comprehensive way
of picking the 25 best players in America,

265
00:15:21,755 --> 00:15:25,300
and you three are certainly
among the very top.

266
00:15:26,051 --> 00:15:31,222
The 1979 McDonald's All American class
was one of the best ever.

267
00:15:31,306 --> 00:15:34,225
[announcer] This year's talent
is set to be just incredible.

268
00:15:34,309 --> 00:15:38,647
The rosters include: Ralph Sampson,
James Worthy, Byron Scott,

269
00:15:38,730 --> 00:15:42,525
Sam Bowie, Clark Kellogg, John Paxson,
Dominique Wilkins

270
00:15:42,609 --> 00:15:45,111
and Isiah Thomas, just to name a few.

271
00:15:45,195 --> 00:15:47,697
Isiah had a reputation
of being a tough kid.

272
00:15:47,781 --> 00:15:50,450
And when he went
to the Ronald McDonald house,

273
00:15:51,159 --> 00:15:52,494
and he saw the kids,

274
00:15:53,078 --> 00:15:56,247
he became very emotional
to the point where he started crying.

275
00:15:59,459 --> 00:16:01,086
That stuck with me.

276
00:16:01,169 --> 00:16:03,672
It's just something
that I always wanted to do.

277
00:16:03,755 --> 00:16:07,300
I always wanted to take time off and
come to the hospital and visit the kids.

278
00:16:07,384 --> 00:16:10,845
I mean… You know, playing basketball,
you never have time to do it,

279
00:16:10,929 --> 00:16:14,265
and I'm glad McDonald's House, you know,
giving us a chance to do this.

280
00:16:14,349 --> 00:16:16,351
Would you like Isiah's name
on your basketball?

281
00:16:16,434 --> 00:16:19,229
-Are you ticklish? [laughs]
-Yeah, she's ticklish.

282
00:16:20,313 --> 00:16:21,731
By the time that game came around,

283
00:16:21,815 --> 00:16:24,651
as excited as we were in Chicago
about Isiah Thomas,

284
00:16:24,734 --> 00:16:29,572
to me, it was about this kid
out of North Carolina

285
00:16:29,656 --> 00:16:33,159
that I don't think anybody really knew
about, and that was Dominique Wilkins.

286
00:16:34,994 --> 00:16:37,872
'Cause you start hearing stories
about kids, like, nah that's just a myth.

287
00:16:37,956 --> 00:16:40,165
And you know how people lie
and embellish shit.

288
00:16:40,250 --> 00:16:42,252
So, you know, you're like, "Oh, this guy…

289
00:16:42,335 --> 00:16:44,713
this kid put his foot on the backboard…"

290
00:16:44,796 --> 00:16:47,674
You know… [chuckles]
It was crazy stories about Dominique.

291
00:16:48,883 --> 00:16:51,344
[Wilkins] I started dunking when I was 13.

292
00:16:51,428 --> 00:16:55,348
And I was the first one in the
neighborhood who dunked 11-foot goal.

293
00:16:55,432 --> 00:16:58,893
Nobody else could do it.
I mean, at 13, I was jumping over cars.

294
00:16:59,894 --> 00:17:03,982
I didn't really get nervous
until the McDonald's game.

295
00:17:04,065 --> 00:17:06,443
The level of talent that was on the floor.

296
00:17:06,526 --> 00:17:09,404
I've never seen that many great players
at one time.

297
00:17:09,487 --> 00:17:11,531
[commentator]
The spotlight dispels the darkness.

298
00:17:11,614 --> 00:17:14,242
As the greatest talent
in high school basketball

299
00:17:14,325 --> 00:17:17,619
ready their extraordinary skill
and superhuman ability.

300
00:17:17,704 --> 00:17:20,790
You wanna get back on defense.
Back on defense.

301
00:17:23,084 --> 00:17:26,880
[Scoop] The talent on the court
that year really elevated

302
00:17:26,963 --> 00:17:30,633
what McDonald's All American
had the possibility of showcasing.

303
00:17:33,178 --> 00:17:35,805
Let's start in the east and
we'll be taking you through each region.

304
00:17:35,889 --> 00:17:37,599
There are 12 teams in each region.

305
00:17:38,183 --> 00:17:40,935
[Silver] In the early days
of the McDonald's All American Game,

306
00:17:41,019 --> 00:17:44,856
the NCAA intervened with a rule announcing

307
00:17:44,939 --> 00:17:46,858
that any player
who played in an All Star game

308
00:17:46,941 --> 00:17:49,486
would never be allowed to play in college.

309
00:17:49,569 --> 00:17:53,031
[Geoghan] I got a call one day
from the NCAA

310
00:17:53,114 --> 00:17:56,075
saying that they were gonna ban
all All Star games

311
00:17:56,159 --> 00:17:59,996
because they had heard
from principals in high school

312
00:18:00,580 --> 00:18:02,957
that kids were missing too much school.

313
00:18:03,041 --> 00:18:09,005
And I asked the NCAA why they thought
they had the right to ban these games.

314
00:18:09,088 --> 00:18:11,090
Why throw the baby out with the bathwater?
I don't…

315
00:18:11,174 --> 00:18:14,636
I don't know how any other All Star game
was run, but I knew how I ran mine.

316
00:18:14,719 --> 00:18:18,431
For six months, I had to spend time
trying to get on the agenda

317
00:18:18,515 --> 00:18:20,058
at the NCAA convention.

318
00:18:20,642 --> 00:18:23,770
[Silver] Bob and I
had to verbally tell them

319
00:18:23,853 --> 00:18:27,190
why we felt that the McDonald's
All American game was special.

320
00:18:27,273 --> 00:18:30,652
And within a week, it was announced

321
00:18:30,735 --> 00:18:34,906
that a senior could play in
two All Star games within a year

322
00:18:34,989 --> 00:18:37,909
and still be eligible for college.

323
00:18:37,992 --> 00:18:40,453
It allowed All Star games to continue.

324
00:18:43,706 --> 00:18:48,503
When finally we all lock in
at the McDonald's game,

325
00:18:48,586 --> 00:18:51,005
you're just like, damn, this is crazy.

326
00:18:51,756 --> 00:18:53,591
You just heard about people,
read about 'em,

327
00:18:53,675 --> 00:18:57,554
so now, I'm like meeting them
and, you know, we enjoying time together

328
00:18:57,637 --> 00:18:59,639
'cause we get to spend it. We going out.

329
00:19:00,223 --> 00:19:03,351
And then we kinda practice, and I'm like,
"All right, here we go. Let me see."

330
00:19:03,434 --> 00:19:05,144
[crowd cheering]

331
00:19:06,729 --> 00:19:12,402
Looking back now, the All American
practice was very intense.

332
00:19:12,485 --> 00:19:14,320
Compared to like a WNBA All Star practice,

333
00:19:14,404 --> 00:19:17,198
which is like, "Oh, ha, ha,
let's do half-court shots."

334
00:19:17,282 --> 00:19:19,909
Um, no, people were going at it.

335
00:19:19,993 --> 00:19:22,620
Everybody knew why one another was here.

336
00:19:23,371 --> 00:19:27,041
Yeah. Practices are always
more interesting than games.

337
00:19:27,125 --> 00:19:29,043
[players grunting, chattering]

338
00:19:37,218 --> 00:19:38,469
[coach] Be tough on 'em.

339
00:19:38,553 --> 00:19:41,723
Be tough so when we play
that West team on… on Wednesday,

340
00:19:41,806 --> 00:19:44,684
we gonna get after them
just like we get after ourselves.

341
00:19:53,443 --> 00:19:55,820
[Stackhouse] I think
you're still competing for, uh, minutes.

342
00:19:55,904 --> 00:19:58,865
There's 12 players on the team,
so Coach gotta decide

343
00:19:58,948 --> 00:20:03,244
who's the cream of the crop amongst this.
No friends right now.

344
00:20:05,872 --> 00:20:09,959
I looked at that week of practice
as, like, another test for me.

345
00:20:10,043 --> 00:20:11,044
How good am I?

346
00:20:11,127 --> 00:20:14,380
And I also remember
it was the first time I became aware

347
00:20:14,464 --> 00:20:17,675
that there were, like,
NBA scouts in the gym.

348
00:20:17,759 --> 00:20:21,137
When the cameras are off
and you're in the gym training

349
00:20:21,220 --> 00:20:24,432
and you got the coaches watching you
and they seeing your work ethic,

350
00:20:24,515 --> 00:20:27,393
they seeing your attitude,
how you treat your teammates.

351
00:20:27,477 --> 00:20:31,314
Those are the small details
that one gotta focus on.

352
00:20:31,397 --> 00:20:34,442
You know, in 2002, there was
this young man you heard a lot about,

353
00:20:34,525 --> 00:20:35,735
Amar'e Stoudemire.

354
00:20:35,818 --> 00:20:38,404
And you'd see footage of him
in high school games,

355
00:20:38,488 --> 00:20:40,073
and he-he looked like Shaq out there.

356
00:20:40,156 --> 00:20:42,909
Like, just dunking all over everybody,
dominating.

357
00:20:43,534 --> 00:20:48,039
And then you look up a little bit later,
he's in the McDonald's All American Game.

358
00:20:49,123 --> 00:20:51,000
[Stoudemire]
"I'm going straight to the league."

359
00:20:51,084 --> 00:20:53,795
That was my thought process,
and I wasn't playing.

360
00:20:53,878 --> 00:20:55,380
I was… I was dead serious.

361
00:20:55,463 --> 00:20:57,590
You got players
trying to challenge you in practice

362
00:20:57,674 --> 00:20:59,759
to try to see
if you're who you think you are.

363
00:20:59,842 --> 00:21:05,223
[JJ Redick] We all knew in our class
that Carmelo and Bosh, Amar'e,

364
00:21:05,306 --> 00:21:09,143
were different than the rest.
Those guys were supreme.

365
00:21:09,227 --> 00:21:12,063
We were all good. Those guys were supreme.

366
00:21:12,146 --> 00:21:14,148
And we all kinda knew that.
Actually, I take that back.

367
00:21:14,232 --> 00:21:16,401
There was one guy
that probably didn't realize that,

368
00:21:16,484 --> 00:21:19,278
'cause he thought he was so good,
but… I don't wanna name names.

369
00:21:20,655 --> 00:21:23,241
[Stoudemire] DeAngelo Collins.
I was hearing rumors about how he…

370
00:21:23,324 --> 00:21:25,159
"He's better than me."
And this, that and the third.

371
00:21:25,243 --> 00:21:29,789
And Amar'e went at him, dominated him
and elevated his stock.

372
00:21:29,872 --> 00:21:32,417
[Stoudemire] It wasn't even a question
who was the man out there.

373
00:21:33,042 --> 00:21:36,379
There was no doubt.
I was in a different mindset.

374
00:21:36,462 --> 00:21:39,257
I'm not doing
the finger roll off the glass move.

375
00:21:39,340 --> 00:21:42,593
I'm attacking the basket,
and I'm shaking the whole backboard.

376
00:21:43,177 --> 00:21:46,139
I think at that point on,
everyone knew at that time, like,

377
00:21:46,222 --> 00:21:48,224
"STAT, he going to the NBA.
He ain't going to college.

378
00:21:48,307 --> 00:21:49,767
This guy going straight to the league."

379
00:21:49,851 --> 00:21:52,020
Yeah, the McDonald's
All American practices…

380
00:21:52,770 --> 00:21:54,230
I mean, by the time we left,

381
00:21:54,313 --> 00:21:57,775
I'm sure there's a few screws and hinges
that might've been left off the rim.

382
00:21:57,859 --> 00:22:01,195
[laughs] Oh, I was
a different kind of beast, man.

383
00:22:01,279 --> 00:22:02,447
[people cheering]

384
00:22:08,578 --> 00:22:10,121
[coach] These fingers are crossed.

385
00:22:11,414 --> 00:22:13,708
[Joe] Gradey Dick.
Everyone told me he was a shooter.

386
00:22:13,791 --> 00:22:15,376
I think he's more than a shooter.

387
00:22:15,460 --> 00:22:17,712
-Dariq is, I think, for sure a pro.
-[coach] Phenomenal.

388
00:22:18,296 --> 00:22:20,256
[Joe] And a phenom… Like, good kid.

389
00:22:20,339 --> 00:22:24,469
[coach] So nice. Because for me
it's like, all these kids are auditioning.

390
00:22:24,552 --> 00:22:26,429
-[Joe] Absolutely.
-[coach] Especially with us.

391
00:22:26,512 --> 00:22:28,723
I just put in my list about who we want.

392
00:22:28,806 --> 00:22:32,894
I was just told
that we're going five more minutes,

393
00:22:32,977 --> 00:22:36,189
'cause there must be somebody out here
they want to take a good look at.

394
00:22:36,272 --> 00:22:39,525
So, if you weren't satisfied
with where you were, fix it.

395
00:22:39,609 --> 00:22:41,652
If you are satisfied,
then you better keep building

396
00:22:41,736 --> 00:22:44,030
because that means maybe you.

397
00:22:44,113 --> 00:22:45,948
So we can get on offense,
and run the court.

398
00:22:46,032 --> 00:22:48,785
Find a point guard,
and let's get out there. You guys got it.

399
00:22:48,868 --> 00:22:50,328
-Yes, sir!
-McDonald's. McDonald's on three.

400
00:22:50,411 --> 00:22:51,621
-One, two, three. McDonald's.
-[players] McDonald's.

401
00:22:51,704 --> 00:22:54,123
-[Lively] Right here!
-You good?

402
00:22:57,794 --> 00:23:00,004
I think Dereck Lively's
more than just a basketball player.

403
00:23:00,088 --> 00:23:03,633
His-His ability to communicate,
his intelligence has been unbelievable.

404
00:23:04,258 --> 00:23:07,095
He can be an ambassador
if he didn't have an NBA career,

405
00:23:07,178 --> 00:23:09,222
which I think he'll be good enough
to have someday.

406
00:23:10,973 --> 00:23:12,517
There's times you may wanna go under.

407
00:23:12,600 --> 00:23:15,895
Right now, in this drill, always over.
Talk.

408
00:23:15,978 --> 00:23:17,396
I'm here to be able to move the rock.

409
00:23:17,480 --> 00:23:20,274
Be able to show
that I can fit into the style of play

410
00:23:20,358 --> 00:23:22,026
that needs to be played in the league.

411
00:23:27,156 --> 00:23:30,743
Hedge it! Hed… There we go!
Yeah! Very good.

412
00:23:32,286 --> 00:23:34,163
[Joe] Flau'jae,
she's got some personality.

413
00:23:34,247 --> 00:23:37,166
And then somebody told me,
"She's that… We're not sure if she's one."

414
00:23:37,250 --> 00:23:39,627
-I'm like, she's-she's without a doubt.
-[coach] Mmm.

415
00:23:41,045 --> 00:23:42,713
[Flau'jae] Nothing was ever given to me.

416
00:23:43,548 --> 00:23:47,343
Coming from Savannah, man,
you see people like… They have nothin'.

417
00:23:47,426 --> 00:23:50,221
Kids in the projects,
they ain't got no shoes on they feet.

418
00:23:50,304 --> 00:23:51,764
They don't know when they goin' eat again.

419
00:23:51,848 --> 00:23:55,101
So, it's like, I've been blessed to have
so many options and so many talents.

420
00:23:55,184 --> 00:23:56,394
I will not take this for granted.

421
00:23:56,978 --> 00:23:58,354
Like, I worked hard.

422
00:23:58,437 --> 00:24:00,731
And then when I felt like I couldn't work
no more, I worked some more.

423
00:24:02,942 --> 00:24:04,986
And being in the studio,
it's like I write every day.

424
00:24:05,069 --> 00:24:08,072
I freestyle every day.
So, I'm like, I'm building up my craft,

425
00:24:08,156 --> 00:24:11,409
and I'm building up everything I'm doing
every day. So, it-it's all gonna pay off.

426
00:24:12,076 --> 00:24:14,620
♪ If you woulda put that gun down
Listen ♪

427
00:24:16,205 --> 00:24:18,166
♪ Do you know what it's like
To not have a father? ♪

428
00:24:18,249 --> 00:24:20,334
♪ No one to talk to
When you get mad at your mama ♪

429
00:24:20,418 --> 00:24:22,962
♪ I know you ain't gone pick up the phone
I still call you ♪

430
00:24:23,045 --> 00:24:25,381
♪ The reason that it hurts so bad
I never saw you ♪

431
00:24:25,464 --> 00:24:26,966
♪♪ If you woulda put that gun down ♪

432
00:24:27,049 --> 00:24:29,594
♪ Everybody put your guns down ♪

433
00:24:29,677 --> 00:24:30,803
[audience cheering]

434
00:24:30,887 --> 00:24:32,680
This has been my favorite audition

435
00:24:32,763 --> 00:24:35,349
-by a clear mile today, Flau'jae.
-Oh, my…

436
00:24:36,559 --> 00:24:40,271
I started off, because before I was born,
my father, he was a rapper.

437
00:24:40,354 --> 00:24:41,397
Yeah.

438
00:24:41,480 --> 00:24:42,607
[Flau'jae] And, um…

439
00:24:44,650 --> 00:24:49,447
[sighs] He died before I was born.
So, he couldn't really fulfill his dreams.

440
00:24:49,530 --> 00:24:51,073
So, that's what I'm here to do.

441
00:24:51,157 --> 00:24:53,576
[reporter] May 19th, rapper Camoflauge
was gunned down…

442
00:24:53,659 --> 00:24:55,203
[reporter 2] It was the worst. It was…

443
00:24:55,286 --> 00:24:57,079
-[reporters overlapping]
-…still to this day,

444
00:24:57,163 --> 00:25:01,959
probably the saddest day
in Savannah. The saddest.

445
00:25:02,043 --> 00:25:04,879
[reporter 3]
Camoflauge friends and fans, stunned.

446
00:25:07,715 --> 00:25:11,302
My dad, Jason, aka Camoflauge,

447
00:25:11,385 --> 00:25:15,681
he was a up-and-coming rapper
out of Savannah, Georgia. Mad talented.

448
00:25:15,765 --> 00:25:17,600
[rap song playing]

449
00:25:20,228 --> 00:25:24,023
Got his break. He signed to
Universal Records when he was, like, 21.

450
00:25:24,106 --> 00:25:28,444
Signed that deal, shortly after, he died.
Like, he got murdered in Savannah.

451
00:25:28,527 --> 00:25:31,489
Um, and my mom was pregnant with me
at the same time.

452
00:25:31,572 --> 00:25:34,158
That same year he got murdered,
my mom was pregnant with me.

453
00:25:34,909 --> 00:25:37,536
And, like, he was on his way, though.

454
00:25:37,620 --> 00:25:39,497
You know what I mean?
Like, he was on his way.

455
00:25:40,498 --> 00:25:42,500
He was talented. Like, he was so talented.

456
00:25:42,583 --> 00:25:45,753
And that's why I feel like it's my duty
to carry on that legacy.

457
00:25:54,345 --> 00:25:56,055
When I was seven, my dad passed away.

458
00:25:58,349 --> 00:26:00,142
It's been me and my mom since then.

459
00:26:00,226 --> 00:26:03,187
And in 2013,
she was diagnosed with cancer.

460
00:26:03,271 --> 00:26:07,984
So, ever since I was young I had to
think about more than just what I wanted.

461
00:26:10,778 --> 00:26:12,697
My mom, she could hoop back in her day.

462
00:26:12,780 --> 00:26:14,365
She used… She scored
a thousand something points,

463
00:26:14,448 --> 00:26:16,200
grabbed over 700 rebounds.

464
00:26:16,284 --> 00:26:18,577
I hear it every other conversation
I have with her.

465
00:26:18,661 --> 00:26:22,373
But being able to have someone that close
who cares about you,

466
00:26:22,456 --> 00:26:26,335
who has your best interests,
and also knows the game perfectly

467
00:26:26,419 --> 00:26:28,963
is someone that you definitely need
to keep in your back pocket.

468
00:26:29,630 --> 00:26:32,300
I know she's going through
the hardest time right now.

469
00:26:32,383 --> 00:26:35,594
Right now she's in the hospital,
and she's gonna be for the next month.

470
00:26:35,678 --> 00:26:40,808
So, I'ma be carrying her weight and
the weight of her future on my shoulders.

471
00:26:40,891 --> 00:26:42,226
-[phone ringing]
-Oh, there we go.

472
00:26:42,310 --> 00:26:44,103
-Oh, there she is.
-Hi, Mom.

473
00:26:44,186 --> 00:26:46,022
-Hi, Mama.
-Hi.

474
00:26:46,105 --> 00:26:47,815
You look beautiful with your glasses, Mom.

475
00:26:47,898 --> 00:26:50,318
[Lively] When she was
going through the hard stuff,

476
00:26:50,401 --> 00:26:55,114
whenever she had to do the chemotherapy,
like, her body reacted so much to that.

477
00:26:55,197 --> 00:26:57,533
And I was the one
who had to take care of her, 'cause she…

478
00:26:57,616 --> 00:26:59,327
Some days
she couldn't even get out of bed.

479
00:26:59,410 --> 00:27:00,870
Extremely proud. Extremely proud.

480
00:27:00,953 --> 00:27:02,371
-I'll text you, Mom. Love you.
-Love you, Kath.

481
00:27:02,455 --> 00:27:03,581
-Okay. Love you.[kisses]
-Love you.

482
00:27:03,664 --> 00:27:06,542
It's humbling to watch
the two of them go through this.

483
00:27:06,625 --> 00:27:09,086
I don't know many families
that could survive what they're doing,

484
00:27:09,170 --> 00:27:10,463
and what they've been through.

485
00:27:15,259 --> 00:27:16,344
You know, she's one of the proudest.

486
00:27:16,427 --> 00:27:20,681
'Cause she was one of the first people
to see little scrawny Dereck that was…

487
00:27:20,765 --> 00:27:22,683
Don't you know, like,
the little car dealerships that have,

488
00:27:22,767 --> 00:27:25,311
like, the blowup machine
that couldn't control his limbs?

489
00:27:25,394 --> 00:27:27,646
Yeah, that was me at the dinner table
when I was younger.

490
00:27:27,730 --> 00:27:29,857
He spilled a glass of milk every night.

491
00:27:29,940 --> 00:27:31,650
-[laughs]
-[chuckles]

492
00:27:32,318 --> 00:27:34,070
The best high school basketball players
in the country

493
00:27:34,153 --> 00:27:38,032
met this weekend in Wichita, Kansas
at the McDonald's All American Games.

494
00:27:38,115 --> 00:27:41,160
Billy Packer went on a solo assignment,
away from his NCAA partners

495
00:27:41,243 --> 00:27:45,081
of Al McGuire and Dick Enberg
to give us this special report. Billy.

496
00:27:46,165 --> 00:27:47,208
[crowd cheering]

497
00:27:47,291 --> 00:27:50,127
Every year, a new group
of high school superstars

498
00:27:50,211 --> 00:27:53,589
from across the country
burst onto the collegiate scene.

499
00:27:53,672 --> 00:27:56,467
This year, once again,
the McDonald's All American team

500
00:27:56,550 --> 00:27:58,344
represents the cream of the crop.

501
00:27:58,427 --> 00:28:00,971
The kids that are sure to be
tomorrow's heroes.

502
00:28:01,055 --> 00:28:03,307
It's hard to believe, but four years ago,

503
00:28:03,391 --> 00:28:06,560
a guy named Magic Johnson
was a McDonald's All American.

504
00:28:06,644 --> 00:28:11,232
Since that time, he's led his team
to the NCAA and NBA championships.

505
00:28:11,315 --> 00:28:15,486
Two years ago, it was Sampson, Bowie
and a little guy named Isiah Thomas.

506
00:28:15,569 --> 00:28:17,822
Yeah, that's the same Thomas that led IU

507
00:28:17,905 --> 00:28:20,366
to the national crown
where he was the MVP.

508
00:28:20,449 --> 00:28:24,120
In fact, in the years…
this year's NCAA championship,

509
00:28:24,203 --> 00:28:27,998
six of the ten starters were former
McDonald's high school All Americans.

510
00:28:28,082 --> 00:28:33,379
I was fortunate to be one of those guys
on the McDonald's All American team.

511
00:28:33,462 --> 00:28:35,631
This year's crop is out of sight.

512
00:28:36,465 --> 00:28:40,636
Some of the best big men we've ever seen.
Two of the best right here.

513
00:28:40,719 --> 00:28:44,265
Pat Ewing, Cambridge, Mass.
Greg Dreiling, Wichita, Kansas.

514
00:28:44,348 --> 00:28:46,851
They've got some skills,
and they're just plain out of sight.

515
00:28:48,144 --> 00:28:51,188
I was offered the opportunity
to coach those all-star games,

516
00:28:51,272 --> 00:28:53,149
and I gladly accepted.

517
00:28:54,108 --> 00:28:56,110
You get this group of kids.

518
00:28:56,193 --> 00:28:58,988
I didn't know who these guys were,
because you didn't hear about them.

519
00:28:59,655 --> 00:29:03,784
I remember this guy, I mean…
He wanted to win every single race.

520
00:29:03,868 --> 00:29:05,786
Every suicide, he was first.

521
00:29:05,870 --> 00:29:07,288
Yeah, I mean, he just refuses…

522
00:29:07,371 --> 00:29:09,165
He don't want to lose anything.
His name's Michael Jordan.

523
00:29:09,248 --> 00:29:13,878
[Packer] We put a giant ruler on them
to check out the young cloud piercers.

524
00:29:13,961 --> 00:29:16,338
First, Michael Jordan, 6'5".

525
00:29:16,422 --> 00:29:18,382
Eight-and-a-half foot reach,

526
00:29:18,466 --> 00:29:21,677
an 11-foot touch,
30 inches off the ground.

527
00:29:22,303 --> 00:29:26,974
I can still remember Michael
just flying up and down the court.

528
00:29:27,057 --> 00:29:29,643
"Wow, this is the most athletic person
I've ever seen in my life.

529
00:29:29,727 --> 00:29:30,853
This guy is different."

530
00:29:30,936 --> 00:29:33,606
[Ewing] I can remember
Michael talking trash.

531
00:29:33,689 --> 00:29:36,734
That's him. That's part of his DNA.
That's part of his personality.

532
00:29:36,817 --> 00:29:40,529
We're both in our 60s now,
and he's still talkin' trash.

533
00:29:40,613 --> 00:29:44,033
And the thing is, we, the east squad,
was the underdog.

534
00:29:44,116 --> 00:29:47,286
They were the home team,
we were the visitors from the east.

535
00:29:47,369 --> 00:29:49,997
We were not supposed to win the game.

536
00:29:51,999 --> 00:29:55,461
We were down early.
Adrian Branch plays his butt off.

537
00:30:00,341 --> 00:30:02,885
We were up two or three
going into the last four or five minutes.

538
00:30:04,720 --> 00:30:05,721
They go ahead.

539
00:30:07,014 --> 00:30:08,474
But then, we got Michael Jordan.

540
00:30:08,557 --> 00:30:11,060
[commentator] It's Jordan on the…
Oh, what a layup!

541
00:30:11,143 --> 00:30:15,564
[Jarvis] The last five possessions
of the game, Michael Jordan hit the shot.

542
00:30:15,648 --> 00:30:17,274
[commentator] Jordan! Michael!

543
00:30:17,358 --> 00:30:19,652
The last one he took
was the last one that put us…

544
00:30:19,735 --> 00:30:22,821
gave us 96 points in a 96-95 victory.

545
00:30:24,740 --> 00:30:27,326
[Hill] When I watch that game,
I'm thinking, like,

546
00:30:27,409 --> 00:30:30,704
"This Mike Jordan seems kinda raw,
but he's the real deal."

547
00:30:30,788 --> 00:30:33,499
Not only did he hit the game winner

548
00:30:33,582 --> 00:30:36,835
to win a national championship
for North Carolina in '82,

549
00:30:36,919 --> 00:30:41,507
but he hit a game winner
to win the McDonald's All American Game.

550
00:30:42,258 --> 00:30:43,926
-[commentator] Shot, Jordan!
-[crowd cheering]

551
00:30:44,009 --> 00:30:48,681
Great shot, great player.
You know, that's what great players do.

552
00:30:48,764 --> 00:30:49,932
[crowd cheering]

553
00:30:52,393 --> 00:30:54,645
[Jarvis] I mean,
I didn't know till years later

554
00:30:54,728 --> 00:30:56,605
that it was a scoring record,
to be honest with you.

555
00:30:56,689 --> 00:30:58,649
And I don't think Michael did either.

556
00:30:58,732 --> 00:31:01,777
It wasn't about scoring.
It was about winning.

557
00:31:02,403 --> 00:31:05,656
I remember saying to Mike,
"Hey, congratulations on the win.

558
00:31:05,739 --> 00:31:07,616
And I know you're gonna get
the MVP award."

559
00:31:08,617 --> 00:31:13,205
[Hill] Adrian Branch
and Audrey Sherrod were co-MVPs.

560
00:31:13,289 --> 00:31:14,331
Not Michael.

561
00:31:14,915 --> 00:31:17,418
I think Michael was the MVP of that game.

562
00:31:18,460 --> 00:31:21,130
[Jarvis] Adrian was the MVP,
and he played great.

563
00:31:21,213 --> 00:31:24,550
But he had something going for him
that Michael Jordan didn't.

564
00:31:24,633 --> 00:31:28,762
His coach, Morgan Wootten,
he was part of the selection committee.

565
00:31:28,846 --> 00:31:29,972
So, that always helps.

566
00:31:31,432 --> 00:31:34,935
After the game, I'm on the elevator
with Mr. and Mrs. Jordan.

567
00:31:35,019 --> 00:31:38,063
And I remember Mrs. Jordan
saying to Billy Packer,

568
00:31:39,064 --> 00:31:42,192
"Poor Michael. My poor son Michael.

569
00:31:42,276 --> 00:31:46,822
He never gets any recognition.
He never gets any respect."

570
00:31:47,823 --> 00:31:52,578
She was pissed.
Um, and right-rightfully so.

571
00:31:52,661 --> 00:31:54,079
Um, but…

572
00:31:55,289 --> 00:31:58,542
Hey. It's water under the bridge now.
[chuckles]

573
00:31:59,627 --> 00:32:00,878
[Scoop] You know, one of the things

574
00:32:00,961 --> 00:32:03,964
that made the McDonald's game so special
and seeing Michael do that is,

575
00:32:04,840 --> 00:32:09,887
quietly, he's letting the world know
just how great he is.

576
00:32:19,521 --> 00:32:21,357
[Geoghan]
I thought the basketball landscape

577
00:32:21,440 --> 00:32:23,942
certainly changed for the better.

578
00:32:24,026 --> 00:32:26,820
And because of ESPN and television,

579
00:32:28,072 --> 00:32:32,242
more people are aware of the game.
And became more popular.

580
00:32:34,036 --> 00:32:37,289
To be selected as one of the top 20
high school players in America…

581
00:32:37,373 --> 00:32:38,374
It will always be…

582
00:32:38,457 --> 00:32:40,250
For the rest of my life
I'm gonna remember this moment.

583
00:32:40,334 --> 00:32:42,628
[Scoop] The ascension
of the McDonald's All American Games

584
00:32:42,711 --> 00:32:47,257
started making Black kids dream earlier

585
00:32:48,258 --> 00:32:51,553
about what the game of basketball
can do to their lives.

586
00:32:53,055 --> 00:32:58,727
And in '85 when McDonald's got
a television partner to televise the game,

587
00:32:58,811 --> 00:33:00,020
it just changed everything.

588
00:33:00,104 --> 00:33:03,732
[Jim Thacker] Welcome to the eighth
annual McDonald's All American Game.

589
00:33:04,400 --> 00:33:06,360
Brought to you by McDonald's.

590
00:33:06,443 --> 00:33:10,072
It's a good time
for the great taste of McDonald's.

591
00:33:10,698 --> 00:33:13,867
I'm Jim Thacker,
and with me is Dick Vitale.

592
00:33:13,951 --> 00:33:16,662
Dick, tell us about the concept
and the importance of this game.

593
00:33:16,745 --> 00:33:19,665
Jim, right now we're gonna have,
really what I call showtime!

594
00:33:19,748 --> 00:33:22,418
It's gonna be prime time performers
at their best.

595
00:33:22,501 --> 00:33:26,839
The talent. People like Magic Johnson,
Ralph Sampson, Patrick Ewing.

596
00:33:26,922 --> 00:33:30,050
All served notice in this game
that their stardom was no dream.

597
00:33:30,134 --> 00:33:31,552
High school All American Game.

598
00:33:31,635 --> 00:33:33,387
The McDonald's All Americans
in just a moment.

599
00:33:33,470 --> 00:33:36,306
With a tip, and it is taken over
to the white-clad West team.

600
00:33:36,390 --> 00:33:37,725
[advertiser 1] But don't salute.

601
00:33:37,808 --> 00:33:40,269
[advertiser 2] The DeLorean
gull-wing doors.

602
00:33:42,855 --> 00:33:43,856
My name is Danny Manning.

603
00:33:43,939 --> 00:33:46,108
I'm from Lawrence, Kansas.
I go to Lawrence High School.

604
00:33:46,191 --> 00:33:48,944
Kenny Smith. Archbishop Molloy
High School. Queens, New York.

605
00:33:49,027 --> 00:33:51,780
[commentator] And the particulars
on the individual here…

606
00:33:51,864 --> 00:33:55,325
[commentator 2] 27 points. A strong
candidate for the John Wooden award.

607
00:33:57,953 --> 00:33:59,413
[advertiser 3] ♪ That big, red box ♪

608
00:33:59,496 --> 00:34:02,833
You know, I study, I do my work
and go to class.

609
00:34:02,916 --> 00:34:07,254
[announcer] From the West, number 43,
Derrick Coleman!

610
00:34:07,337 --> 00:34:09,505
There's an enormous amount of talent.

611
00:34:09,590 --> 00:34:12,217
It seems each year
they get bigger and better.

612
00:34:12,301 --> 00:34:14,678
And you can't expect good team play,

613
00:34:14,762 --> 00:34:17,806
because they haven't had a opportunity
to work together.

614
00:34:17,889 --> 00:34:20,058
I have said this
and believe it to be true,

615
00:34:20,141 --> 00:34:23,771
that television,
of which you're a tremendous part,

616
00:34:23,853 --> 00:34:27,858
has, uh, caused many players
to become more individual.

617
00:34:27,940 --> 00:34:31,235
Because they like to be spectacular,
and they like to perform.

618
00:34:31,320 --> 00:34:32,404
Thank you. Coach John Wooden.

619
00:34:32,487 --> 00:34:35,699
Now, let's join Dick Vitale
and a couple of trees.

620
00:34:35,783 --> 00:34:37,284
Well, I'll tell you, Keith,
I wanna come back

621
00:34:37,367 --> 00:34:40,161
and retire from the television world
and go to coaching.

622
00:34:40,245 --> 00:34:41,746
Look at these two talents.

623
00:34:41,830 --> 00:34:44,458
I remember being like,
"Wow, I'ma be on national TV, man.

624
00:34:44,541 --> 00:34:46,376
I can… We gotta put on a show."

625
00:34:46,460 --> 00:34:48,085
You know? We gotta put on a show.

626
00:34:48,170 --> 00:34:50,755
[Dick] Start with Alonzo Mourning,
the shot-blockin' wiz.

627
00:34:50,839 --> 00:34:54,510
The Hoya. He's a tremendous talent
with great rejection ability.

628
00:34:54,592 --> 00:34:59,556
How much rejection ability?
27 blocked shots in one game.

629
00:34:59,640 --> 00:35:01,099
[commentator] Moves it the other way!

630
00:35:04,353 --> 00:35:06,104
[Vitale]
Look, Bob Hurley's flashing signals.

631
00:35:06,188 --> 00:35:07,898
-Bob Hurley says, "We want the two-play."
-[laughs]

632
00:35:07,981 --> 00:35:11,318
They'll look and say, "What two-play?
This is all-star. Let me shoot the rock."

633
00:35:12,110 --> 00:35:14,196
[Mourning] We had a stacked class.

634
00:35:14,279 --> 00:35:19,952
Twelve of these 24 players
stand 6'9" or better.

635
00:35:20,035 --> 00:35:23,956
The length, the athleticism,
the skill level.

636
00:35:24,039 --> 00:35:27,626
There was Christian Laettner,
Stanley Roberts, Chris Jackson,

637
00:35:27,709 --> 00:35:31,004
Mahmoud, Billy Owens, Shawn Kemp.

638
00:35:31,088 --> 00:35:36,677
In '88, the talent…
It just felt like it was really elevated.

639
00:35:37,678 --> 00:35:40,681
I had a target on my back.
Those guys were coming at me.

640
00:35:40,764 --> 00:35:44,393
-[crowd cheering]
-[Vitale] There… Kemp! Power move.

641
00:35:44,476 --> 00:35:48,230
Go, Kemp. Shawn Kemp from out of Elkhart…

642
00:35:48,313 --> 00:35:51,733
Then, Shawn Kemp
was one of the most athletic, big men

643
00:35:51,817 --> 00:35:53,735
I'd ever seen in my life.

644
00:35:53,819 --> 00:35:56,071
[Vitale] Look at that talent.
Rebound, handle the rock…

645
00:35:56,154 --> 00:35:59,116
Look at him handle it! Look at this kid!
Are you serious?

646
00:35:59,199 --> 00:36:03,036
Are you for real?
That's a superstar potential!

647
00:36:03,120 --> 00:36:05,080
These kids are solid gold players.

648
00:36:05,163 --> 00:36:07,207
I think when they play
on a collegiate level,

649
00:36:07,291 --> 00:36:09,209
they are instant impact players.

650
00:36:09,293 --> 00:36:12,546
Mourning is such a dominator.
His intimidation ability…

651
00:36:12,629 --> 00:36:16,049
I believe he has a great chance to be
the first high school player

652
00:36:16,133 --> 00:36:17,801
to make the United States Olympic team.

653
00:36:17,885 --> 00:36:19,803
And not just because
John Thompson's the coach.

654
00:36:19,887 --> 00:36:24,683
I get a call from Coach Thompson saying
that there's a young man that we need.

655
00:36:24,766 --> 00:36:30,230
Alonzo Mourning is his name,
and he's a huge fan of yours.

656
00:36:30,814 --> 00:36:32,608
"You can't say anything to him,

657
00:36:32,691 --> 00:36:35,027
but I just want to make sure
that he sees you."

658
00:36:35,110 --> 00:36:39,615
I just walk across the floor, and say,
"What's up." [laughs]

659
00:36:40,449 --> 00:36:44,244
And kept going.
Aw, he's sitting there like… [gasps]

660
00:36:44,328 --> 00:36:45,329
[laughs]

661
00:36:45,412 --> 00:36:50,292
That class in particular, you know,
had some real, real heavyweights

662
00:36:50,375 --> 00:36:52,336
and real talented players.

663
00:36:52,419 --> 00:36:55,923
And so now,
all these coaches are competing.

664
00:36:56,006 --> 00:36:59,760
Not just on the court, but they're
competing, uh, with recruiting.

665
00:37:00,594 --> 00:37:04,932
And, uh… And some, you know, some teams
and some coaches crossed that line.

666
00:37:06,058 --> 00:37:08,352
Maybe more than we… than we know.

667
00:37:08,435 --> 00:37:09,686
-[crowd cheering]
-[Keith] This gets me,

668
00:37:09,770 --> 00:37:12,731
very quickly, into an area
of college athletics that I despise.

669
00:37:12,814 --> 00:37:14,232
I think most coaches do too.

670
00:37:14,316 --> 00:37:17,569
It's the confounded necessity
of recruiting,

671
00:37:17,653 --> 00:37:19,321
and the mess it brings with it.

672
00:37:19,404 --> 00:37:21,156
Oh, you know,
recruiting back in those days,

673
00:37:21,239 --> 00:37:23,700
uh, for everybody who's seen
the movie Blue Chips.

674
00:37:23,784 --> 00:37:26,495
[Ricky] I figure a white,
blue chip athlete like myself

675
00:37:26,578 --> 00:37:28,872
deserves something extra.
About-about 30 grand.

676
00:37:29,623 --> 00:37:32,084
-I'd like to have it in cash.
-Get the hell out of here, Ricky.

677
00:37:32,167 --> 00:37:33,168
-What…
-Get out of here!

678
00:37:33,251 --> 00:37:35,128
All the other schools are doing it, Coach.

679
00:37:35,212 --> 00:37:37,965
[Pete] I did not authorize
a car for Ricky.

680
00:37:38,048 --> 00:37:40,133
[Ed] But you did authorize
the friends of the program

681
00:37:40,217 --> 00:37:41,301
to do what had to be done.

682
00:37:42,052 --> 00:37:44,554
Accurate. Like, you know?
That's just how it was going,

683
00:37:44,638 --> 00:37:48,517
and I'll never be somebody to be salty
at a guy for getting their bag, right?

684
00:37:48,600 --> 00:37:51,186
So, I look at a guy like Chris Mills.
He was the man.

685
00:37:51,269 --> 00:37:53,230
[Vitale] Mills's situation
going on with Kentucky.

686
00:37:53,313 --> 00:37:55,065
[Keith] Yeah,
one of the air freight companies,

687
00:37:55,148 --> 00:37:57,567
one of the employees found, uh,
a package. It was opened.

688
00:37:57,651 --> 00:38:01,363
Intended for the father of Chris Mills
from the University of Kentucky.

689
00:38:01,446 --> 00:38:04,491
They found inside $1,000.

690
00:38:04,574 --> 00:38:09,830
The NCAA showed up, um,
and insisted on interviewing Chris Mills

691
00:38:09,913 --> 00:38:13,667
to talk about the, uh, accusation

692
00:38:13,750 --> 00:38:17,587
that Chris Mills was involved
in a bribery scandal.

693
00:38:17,671 --> 00:38:20,382
There was no evidence to suggest
that he shouldn't play,

694
00:38:20,465 --> 00:38:21,967
'cause Chris didn't know anything
about it.

695
00:38:22,050 --> 00:38:25,554
This was between an assistant coach
and Chris's father.

696
00:38:25,637 --> 00:38:27,597
[Keith] Claud Mills says
he did not receive any money.

697
00:38:27,681 --> 00:38:31,143
The Kentucky people say that
they did not send any money.

698
00:38:31,226 --> 00:38:33,645
I'ma go ahead and say it,
I don't know what happened to the $1,000.

699
00:38:33,729 --> 00:38:35,439
Same thing what happened to me.
Like, no, I never got here.

700
00:38:35,522 --> 00:38:38,233
I don't know what y'all talking about.
I don't know where that rack is at.

701
00:38:38,316 --> 00:38:41,862
That, to me, was just normal, you know,

702
00:38:41,945 --> 00:38:44,489
every day
in the high school recruiting wars.

703
00:38:44,573 --> 00:38:47,701
You know. They all got paid,
and I'm totally fine with it.

704
00:38:47,784 --> 00:38:49,161
[Gary Bender] We're just about set now

705
00:38:49,244 --> 00:38:51,955
to begin the 12th annual
McDonald's All American Game.

706
00:38:52,039 --> 00:38:53,874
Now, for the introduction
of the starting lineups,

707
00:38:53,957 --> 00:38:55,792
the PA announcer, Kevin Harlan.

708
00:38:55,876 --> 00:38:59,796
Back in the day, it's the unknown
that's showing up to the McDonald's game.

709
00:38:59,880 --> 00:39:02,799
So, Matt Wenstrom walks in.
I'm like, okay, he's a big guy, you know?

710
00:39:02,883 --> 00:39:04,760
Then I look. I'm like… [breathes heavily]

711
00:39:04,843 --> 00:39:06,803
"Damn, this dude is huge."

712
00:39:06,887 --> 00:39:08,138
It was Shaquille O'Neal,

713
00:39:08,847 --> 00:39:15,437
and it was the perfect opportunity
for Shaq to say, "Here I am."

714
00:39:15,520 --> 00:39:17,606
When I was getting ready to leave,
he grabbed me and said,

715
00:39:17,689 --> 00:39:18,899
"How long you been in the army, soldier?"

716
00:39:18,982 --> 00:39:20,859
I said, "I'm not in the army.
I'm only 13."

717
00:39:20,942 --> 00:39:22,944
-He started freaking out.
-Oh-- I'll tell you one thing…

718
00:39:23,028 --> 00:39:24,654
[Johnson] His first interview
with Dick Vitale,

719
00:39:24,738 --> 00:39:27,866
you could kind of see the makings
of the Shaq persona that we see now.

720
00:39:27,949 --> 00:39:30,327
Always the jokester,
always trying to keep the mood light…

721
00:39:30,410 --> 00:39:32,829
-Thanks, Shaquille.
-…but a ferocious beast out on the court.

722
00:39:33,830 --> 00:39:35,707
[Rose] I heard about Shaq,

723
00:39:35,791 --> 00:39:41,296
but I didn't physically get a chance to
watch him play until he got in that game.

724
00:39:41,379 --> 00:39:43,215
And he showed so many people,

725
00:39:43,298 --> 00:39:47,219
I can be big and physical,
but I can play with finesse.

726
00:39:48,470 --> 00:39:52,974
[Murray] When Shaq blocked the shot,
we had a three-on-one break.

727
00:39:53,058 --> 00:39:57,312
I'm running the right side, so I'm like,
"Oh, I'm about to dunk on this dude."

728
00:39:57,938 --> 00:40:01,650
Shaq just put it in overdrive
and dunked on Shaun Golden

729
00:40:01,733 --> 00:40:03,443
like he wasn't even there.

730
00:40:03,527 --> 00:40:07,072
The crowd went crazy,
but Dick Vitale lost his mind.

731
00:40:07,155 --> 00:40:09,324
[Vitale] Look at this guy
handling the ball! I can't believe it!

732
00:40:09,407 --> 00:40:11,535
[Bender] He'll take it all the way!
Oh! Oh!

733
00:40:11,618 --> 00:40:14,121
[Vitale] Oh! Oh! Oh! I can't believe it!
I can't believe it!

734
00:40:14,204 --> 00:40:18,041
That's a seven-footer!
Are you serious? [chuckles]

735
00:40:18,125 --> 00:40:20,377
Down on the ground! Are you serious?

736
00:40:20,460 --> 00:40:22,254
-Gary, hold me back, man.
-[Bender chuckles]

737
00:40:22,337 --> 00:40:25,799
I'm still jumping in my seat here.
Most NBA guys can't do this.

738
00:40:27,509 --> 00:40:29,136
I was like, "Oh, my, uh…" [stammers]

739
00:40:29,219 --> 00:40:31,680
I-I thought I was going to get the pass
for the dunk, but when he did,

740
00:40:31,763 --> 00:40:33,056
I was like, "Ooh-wee."

741
00:40:33,140 --> 00:40:38,812
That was something at his size
that we just had not seen.

742
00:40:39,396 --> 00:40:42,232
And to see a guy coming up
like a locomotive…

743
00:40:42,315 --> 00:40:45,986
[stammers] As a guard, you thinking,
"I'ma try swipe at this thing,

744
00:40:46,069 --> 00:40:48,196
but at some point,
I'm getting out of his way."

745
00:40:48,280 --> 00:40:51,199
Shaq wasn't the only breakout star
that night.

746
00:40:51,283 --> 00:40:54,661
There was this kid
from Jersey City, New Jersey.

747
00:40:54,744 --> 00:40:55,871
[Bender] Bob Hurley Jr,

748
00:40:55,954 --> 00:40:59,374
who a lot of people rate as one of
the top ten players in the United States.

749
00:40:59,457 --> 00:41:00,959
[Vitale] Give it up, Bobby. Give it up!

750
00:41:01,042 --> 00:41:03,670
-[Bender] Hurley puts it up.
-[Vitale] There it is! There it is!

751
00:41:03,753 --> 00:41:05,922
[Bender] Tracy Murray
gets it out to Robinson.

752
00:41:06,006 --> 00:41:08,008
-[Vitale] See, Robinson's a scorer.
-[Bender] Look out!

753
00:41:08,091 --> 00:41:09,176
[whistle blows]

754
00:41:09,259 --> 00:41:11,428
And he's going to be called for a charge.

755
00:41:11,511 --> 00:41:13,513
He gets up, slaps the floor.

756
00:41:13,597 --> 00:41:16,933
Hurley showed some courage,
staying in there and drawing the foul.

757
00:41:17,017 --> 00:41:20,604
We were all wondering,
"What the hell was Bobby thinking,

758
00:41:20,687 --> 00:41:23,064
getting in front of a train
and just standing there?"

759
00:41:23,148 --> 00:41:27,444
But, you know what? That showed his heart.
You know, showed that Jersey toughness.

760
00:41:27,527 --> 00:41:28,570
I-I tell you what.

761
00:41:28,653 --> 00:41:31,823
I-I guess I learned the difference
between Bobby Hurley and me,

762
00:41:31,907 --> 00:41:33,450
because I wasn't going to do that.

763
00:41:33,533 --> 00:41:34,534
[Vitale] Look at him right here.

764
00:41:34,618 --> 00:41:36,828
He says, "Come on, big fella.
Run me over. Run me over."

765
00:41:36,912 --> 00:41:37,996
[Bender chuckles]

766
00:41:39,831 --> 00:41:43,293
[JJ Redick] Bobby went to Duke
because Coach K recruited kids

767
00:41:43,376 --> 00:41:46,463
that were sick and demented like him.

768
00:41:46,546 --> 00:41:49,299
You know? That's why me recruited me.
[laughs]

769
00:41:50,300 --> 00:41:53,220
[Murray] And Shaq kind of laughed
and hit the floor

770
00:41:53,303 --> 00:41:54,888
and got up and ran down the floor.

771
00:41:54,971 --> 00:41:57,015
[Bender] …the assist today,
tying the record,

772
00:41:57,098 --> 00:41:58,391
and here comes the 6'11" giant.

773
00:41:58,475 --> 00:41:59,559
[Vitale] Look at the crowd.

774
00:41:59,643 --> 00:42:02,771
They're loving Shaquille O'Neal,
the most valuable player.

775
00:42:02,854 --> 00:42:06,816
[Bender] And the East MVP
is gonna be Bobby Hurley.

776
00:42:06,900 --> 00:42:08,860
A six-footer and a seven-footer

777
00:42:08,944 --> 00:42:12,113
representing this 12th annual
McDonald's All American Game.

778
00:42:20,789 --> 00:42:22,958
Duke, you know,
won that championship in '91.

779
00:42:23,041 --> 00:42:25,377
In '91, they had
six McDonald's All Americans.

780
00:42:25,460 --> 00:42:29,297
That equals the all-time total
that North Carolina had back in '82,

781
00:42:29,381 --> 00:42:30,715
when they had six.

782
00:42:30,799 --> 00:42:33,093
And every team
that's won the national championship

783
00:42:33,176 --> 00:42:36,012
have had at least
one McDonald's All American on it.

784
00:42:36,096 --> 00:42:37,347
[crowd chanting]

785
00:42:37,430 --> 00:42:41,726
[chuckles] I remember where I was
watching the '91 McDonald's game.

786
00:42:41,810 --> 00:42:46,731
We had just won our first championship
at Duke on a Monday,

787
00:42:46,815 --> 00:42:48,233
and the game came on on Sunday.

788
00:42:48,316 --> 00:42:49,859
Like, it was just, like, first of all,

789
00:42:49,943 --> 00:42:54,072
there was some incredible talent
on the floor in that game.

790
00:42:54,155 --> 00:42:58,285
But then, to see, you know, the four guys
that were all going to Michigan,

791
00:42:58,368 --> 00:43:00,578
um, that was unheard of.

792
00:43:03,123 --> 00:43:06,293
[reporter] Contrary to popular belief,
the shift in American basketball

793
00:43:06,376 --> 00:43:07,711
didn't begin in Michigan.

794
00:43:07,794 --> 00:43:13,466
It was 1991 when the Fab Four
first took the floor together

795
00:43:13,550 --> 00:43:15,468
at the McDonald's All American Game.

796
00:43:16,428 --> 00:43:18,596
Four of us, other than Ray Jackson,

797
00:43:18,680 --> 00:43:21,474
each got invited to play
in the McDonald's All American Game,

798
00:43:21,558 --> 00:43:27,188
so we ended up finding a room where
C-Webb and I, and, uh, Jimmy and Juwan

799
00:43:27,272 --> 00:43:31,401
were basically sharing rooms
that were divided by a bathroom.

800
00:43:32,068 --> 00:43:35,196
And that's where we literally devised
all of the thoughts

801
00:43:35,280 --> 00:43:38,199
that we were gonna become the Fab Five
and change the game.

802
00:43:38,825 --> 00:43:40,744
It's hard to ever repeat that

803
00:43:40,827 --> 00:43:44,956
because that's the introduction
to what we be talking about the culture.

804
00:43:45,040 --> 00:43:49,794
Now, what you see in basketball culture
today stemmed from those guys.

805
00:43:52,630 --> 00:43:54,424
Them boys was from the streets.

806
00:43:54,507 --> 00:43:58,136
They bought their confidence,
they bought they haircuts.

807
00:43:58,219 --> 00:43:59,304
They represented, like,

808
00:43:59,387 --> 00:44:03,767
what kids that appreciated the game
in the streets represented.

809
00:44:03,850 --> 00:44:07,228
So, for us to see that on the court,
that was when culture flipped.

810
00:44:08,313 --> 00:44:09,314
[Packer] Chris Webber.

811
00:44:09,397 --> 00:44:11,900
[Gumbel] Billy, he's got
a pro-type body right now.

812
00:44:11,983 --> 00:44:13,443
[Packer] He certainly does.

813
00:44:13,526 --> 00:44:16,112
-[players shouting]
-[crowd cheering]

814
00:44:17,572 --> 00:44:19,366
[Hill] The early '90s McDonald's games

815
00:44:19,449 --> 00:44:23,953
showcased a dramatic shift
in style of play from previous years.

816
00:44:24,037 --> 00:44:25,705
[Packer speaks indistinctly]

817
00:44:26,581 --> 00:44:30,001
[Rose] A lot of people
in that game in 1991

818
00:44:30,085 --> 00:44:32,962
embodied what we now call
positionless basketball.

819
00:44:33,922 --> 00:44:36,508
C-Webb, throw it for a guard
to catch a lob.

820
00:44:38,385 --> 00:44:39,719
[player] Let's go, baby!

821
00:44:39,803 --> 00:44:41,763
[Rose] It may seem normal now…

822
00:44:42,806 --> 00:44:43,848
[Gumbel] Excellent timing.

823
00:44:43,932 --> 00:44:45,934
You can see Rose looking one way,
throwing the other.

824
00:44:46,017 --> 00:44:47,352
Robinson puts it away.

825
00:44:47,435 --> 00:44:52,774
[Rose] Uh, Big Dog, 6'9", 6'10",
played all facing the basket.

826
00:44:52,857 --> 00:44:58,613
He caught one of the nastiest tip dunks
in the history of the McDonald's game.

827
00:44:58,696 --> 00:45:02,325
-[Packer] Robinson…
-[Gumbel] Oh, man! Robinson!

828
00:45:03,034 --> 00:45:07,038
[Rose] We were actually recruiting
The Big Dog to come to Michigan.

829
00:45:07,122 --> 00:45:09,916
You know why? Most times now,
players pick a team where,

830
00:45:09,999 --> 00:45:12,335
"I can go be the man.
I'ma go average my numbers,

831
00:45:12,419 --> 00:45:14,129
and I'ma go to the league."

832
00:45:14,212 --> 00:45:16,381
We were like,
"We're about to try change the game."

833
00:45:16,464 --> 00:45:18,716
[Packer] All the future Michigan players
were kidding Glenn Robinson…

834
00:45:18,800 --> 00:45:21,678
"Well, you go to Purdue, you're going to
have to play in the low post." [chuckles]

835
00:45:21,761 --> 00:45:24,973
[Gumbel] Off to Nathan.
Back to Webber. Nice play!

836
00:45:25,056 --> 00:45:26,057
Yeah!

837
00:45:26,141 --> 00:45:29,060
[Packer] At the rate that Webber
is going right now, take a look.

838
00:45:29,144 --> 00:45:33,189
Just six points shy of the single-game
high set by Michael Jordan.

839
00:45:33,773 --> 00:45:37,694
Best launches a three.
Oh, yes! And ties it!

840
00:45:37,777 --> 00:45:39,904
[crowd cheering]

841
00:45:39,988 --> 00:45:44,617
You see the time remaining.
No foul? Webb--

842
00:45:45,285 --> 00:45:47,203
-Exclamation point.
-[announcer] Webber!

843
00:45:47,287 --> 00:45:49,080
[Packer] They're not gonna
get it up in time.

844
00:45:49,831 --> 00:45:53,418
Best will launch a three-pointer,
but he doesn't get it off in time!

845
00:45:54,169 --> 00:45:58,006
Some finish. And it's over.
As Chris Webber dropped in 28 points.

846
00:45:59,340 --> 00:46:02,969
[Scoop] I think you saw
four brothers who realized,

847
00:46:03,052 --> 00:46:05,263
you know, we kinda look at life
kind of like the same way,

848
00:46:05,346 --> 00:46:07,849
even though our backgrounds
are all kinda different.

849
00:46:07,932 --> 00:46:13,313
They all believe in being unapologetic
about who they are.

850
00:46:14,147 --> 00:46:16,316
That's the one common thread
all of them share.

851
00:46:17,442 --> 00:46:21,446
Their connection
at the McDonald's All American Game

852
00:46:21,529 --> 00:46:23,448
was much deeper than just basketball.

853
00:46:24,616 --> 00:46:26,242
[crowd cheering]

854
00:46:27,035 --> 00:46:29,496
[commentator] This is…
This is quite a group of friends here.

855
00:46:29,579 --> 00:46:32,207
[Paul Pierce] I remember we was watching
in my bed in my bedroom.

856
00:46:33,541 --> 00:46:34,751
These are the top scorers.

857
00:46:35,585 --> 00:46:37,003
I told one of my best friends,

858
00:46:37,086 --> 00:46:39,005
I said, "All right, watch.
I'm gonna be in this game."

859
00:46:39,088 --> 00:46:40,298
That was my first dream.

860
00:46:40,965 --> 00:46:45,136
Check this out. Got the autographed jersey
too. [clicks tongue] Looking sweet.

861
00:46:46,221 --> 00:46:48,014
You know what I'm saying?
About to go in this game,

862
00:46:48,097 --> 00:46:50,058
do a little something-something.

863
00:46:50,141 --> 00:46:53,686
All right, say hi, Mom.
And to my boys at Inglewood, what's up?

864
00:46:53,770 --> 00:46:57,148
We all knew about each other,
so, when we all got to Mickey D's,

865
00:46:57,232 --> 00:46:59,317
it was just good
to be around everybody, you know?

866
00:46:59,400 --> 00:47:03,488
Everybody was confident,
everybody represented where they was from.

867
00:47:03,571 --> 00:47:04,989
I'll never forget those moments.

868
00:47:07,075 --> 00:47:09,744
[Shammgod] People always asked,
"Man, why you have Band-Aids on that ear?"

869
00:47:09,827 --> 00:47:12,205
But it was because I always said
I wanted to get my ears pierced.

870
00:47:12,288 --> 00:47:14,791
And they was like,
"Ah, man, let's-let's all go do it."

871
00:47:14,874 --> 00:47:15,959
So I'm like, "Come on, let's go."

872
00:47:16,543 --> 00:47:18,545
At that point, you couldn't play
with the earrings in,

873
00:47:18,628 --> 00:47:21,089
so we all had to put Band-Aids
over our ears.

874
00:47:22,048 --> 00:47:23,424
I don't remember who all did it,

875
00:47:23,508 --> 00:47:27,554
but I do remember the discussion happened
and then them going

876
00:47:27,637 --> 00:47:30,098
and then everybody coming back
with this tape on their ears and shit.

877
00:47:30,181 --> 00:47:34,435
I'm like, "Oh, y'all did that."
[chuckles] "Okay."

878
00:47:35,103 --> 00:47:36,646
[commentator] By the way, uh,
somebody who had

879
00:47:36,729 --> 00:47:40,692
the ear piercing concession in St. Louis
is probably bound for vacation.

880
00:47:40,775 --> 00:47:44,946
That was, like, my first time.
Like, I watched the game.

881
00:47:45,029 --> 00:47:47,115
I remember, you know,
just turning on the TV

882
00:47:47,198 --> 00:47:52,161
and seeing Paul Pierce, Stephon Marbury,
Shammgod, Kevin Garnett,

883
00:47:52,245 --> 00:47:55,164
his energy, Robert "Tractor" Traylor,
Vince Carter.

884
00:47:55,248 --> 00:48:00,461
We watched that tape over and over
and over and over again,

885
00:48:00,545 --> 00:48:03,548
and that was kind of, like,
all right, if this is the go,

886
00:48:03,631 --> 00:48:06,801
this is the measure, like,
I gotta get in this game.

887
00:48:16,311 --> 00:48:17,937
And for the West,
a young man who's attracted

888
00:48:18,021 --> 00:48:21,065
an enormous amount of attention this year,
Kevin Garnett out of Chicago.

889
00:48:21,149 --> 00:48:22,942
And what a personality.

890
00:48:23,026 --> 00:48:25,111
[Billups] You know,
when I seen KG for the first time,

891
00:48:25,194 --> 00:48:27,572
I'm thinking,
"This motherfucker's crazy, man."

892
00:48:27,655 --> 00:48:30,908
He talking crazy to everybody,
he talking crazy to his self.

893
00:48:31,576 --> 00:48:34,412
I never seen that type
of intensity every day.

894
00:48:34,495 --> 00:48:36,456
[crowd cheering]

895
00:48:36,539 --> 00:48:37,582
Yelling after every block.

896
00:48:37,665 --> 00:48:40,501
I'm talking about sweat everywhere,
it's dripping on you. You're like…

897
00:48:40,585 --> 00:48:43,046
He yelling, spit coming out his mouth.

898
00:48:43,129 --> 00:48:45,256
"Give me that! Give that out of here!"

899
00:48:45,340 --> 00:48:47,258
I'm like, man,
I've never seen nothing like that,

900
00:48:47,342 --> 00:48:49,636
so instantly, you know,
he just raised the level of play.

901
00:48:49,719 --> 00:48:52,889
[Raftery] Goes to BJ McKie and-- Whoa!

902
00:48:52,972 --> 00:48:55,683
[speaks indistinctly] He give him a ten?

903
00:48:56,351 --> 00:48:59,187
Greatest handle since the Messiah.

904
00:49:00,396 --> 00:49:01,856
-Marbury.
-Whoa!

905
00:49:01,939 --> 00:49:03,858
[Raftery] The other end,
here's Louis Bullock.

906
00:49:04,525 --> 00:49:06,402
[crowd cheering]

907
00:49:06,486 --> 00:49:08,321
[Pierce] I was kind of shocked
that I didn't start.

908
00:49:08,404 --> 00:49:09,906
You know, I made best in the West

909
00:49:09,989 --> 00:49:12,116
and I'm not even starting
on the West team?

910
00:49:12,200 --> 00:49:13,493
When I did get in the game, you know,

911
00:49:13,576 --> 00:49:15,536
I wanted to make sure
that my presence was felt.

912
00:49:15,620 --> 00:49:18,581
[Raftery] And it's Paul Pierce
who's on the floor instead of McCoy.

913
00:49:18,665 --> 00:49:20,625
They're both out there.
Well, this is interesting.

914
00:49:20,708 --> 00:49:22,835
But that day,
I know there's a lot of confusion.

915
00:49:22,919 --> 00:49:27,256
I had the… the Jelani McCoy jersey so
they probably gave him some of my points.

916
00:49:27,340 --> 00:49:28,424
[Raftery] Well, there's two 35

917
00:49:28,508 --> 00:49:31,427
because one was stolen
and they had two for McCoy.

918
00:49:31,511 --> 00:49:34,097
So, when we got to
McDonald's All American Game,

919
00:49:34,180 --> 00:49:36,391
everybody's like,
"There's some jerseys missing."

920
00:49:36,474 --> 00:49:38,226
Yeah, people stole some jerseys.

921
00:49:38,309 --> 00:49:41,729
[Raftery] Jelani McCoy, the real McCoy,
is back on the floor now, number 35.

922
00:49:41,813 --> 00:49:46,234
The other McCoy's also out there,
Paul Pierce. It is confusing though.

923
00:49:46,901 --> 00:49:51,072
[Davis] We was watching here in LA,
you know, just rooting for Paul.

924
00:49:51,155 --> 00:49:52,824
We knew, like, he was going for a record.

925
00:49:54,117 --> 00:49:56,411
We was counting his points
'cause we was like,

926
00:49:56,494 --> 00:50:00,081
yo, like, Paul gonna have more points
than Jordan in this game.

927
00:50:01,040 --> 00:50:04,836
[Raftery] Underneath,
stolen by the West at the other end…

928
00:50:04,919 --> 00:50:06,921
[Pierce] I was getting
buckets in the game.

929
00:50:07,004 --> 00:50:08,214
[Raftery] Got it.

930
00:50:14,095 --> 00:50:16,514
But the statisticians, they don't know.
They just hear McCoy.

931
00:50:16,597 --> 00:50:17,932
And they're giving it to him.

932
00:50:18,015 --> 00:50:23,146
[Raftery] The other end of the 35
is Jelani McCoy. He's bound for UCLA.

933
00:50:23,229 --> 00:50:25,398
All these years,
they got Paul Pierce on the record.

934
00:50:25,481 --> 00:50:28,776
These the top scorers. Michael Jordan
was first for a long time, 30.

935
00:50:28,860 --> 00:50:32,739
Then I had 28, I think Webber had, like,
28 or something. It was up there.

936
00:50:32,822 --> 00:50:37,452
I done went back and watched the game
'cause I had the VHS tape at the time.

937
00:50:37,535 --> 00:50:39,996
I want to make sure… I…
Look, man, hold on, I know I ain't…

938
00:50:40,079 --> 00:50:41,164
My eyes ain't deceiving me.

939
00:50:41,247 --> 00:50:44,500
Because when I'm counting these up,
this look like I got 30.

940
00:50:44,584 --> 00:50:46,335
[crowd cheering]

941
00:50:46,961 --> 00:50:48,337
[Raftery] Final five seconds.

942
00:50:48,421 --> 00:50:51,632
Paul definitely broke the scoring record.
Even…

943
00:50:51,716 --> 00:50:53,176
I don't know if he got credit for that,

944
00:50:53,259 --> 00:50:54,802
but he definitely broke
the scoring record.

945
00:50:54,886 --> 00:50:56,679
[Raftery] And look at Pierce get back too.

946
00:50:56,763 --> 00:51:00,016
I mean, making jumpers, it's the end
of the game, and he ran back…

947
00:51:00,600 --> 00:51:02,477
If Paul actually broke that record,

948
00:51:03,686 --> 00:51:06,647
he might be running around today
saying that he's better than MJ.

949
00:51:07,315 --> 00:51:10,109
He just might. I'm just telling you now.

950
00:51:10,193 --> 00:51:13,738
So, I really wanna get
to the bottom of that. [laughs]

951
00:51:13,821 --> 00:51:16,741
[Raftery] Fans rejoice.
So long from St. Louis.

952
00:51:16,824 --> 00:51:18,493
…I'm up here chillin'.

953
00:51:18,576 --> 00:51:21,996
[Pierce] After the game, I remember
all the talk is like, dang, you know,

954
00:51:22,079 --> 00:51:23,831
"Where Kevin going to school?

955
00:51:23,915 --> 00:51:26,751
You know, there's rumors,
North Carolina, Michigan."

956
00:51:26,834 --> 00:51:28,544
But he ain't even really saying.

957
00:51:28,628 --> 00:51:31,297
At the McDonald's game,
we just kinda sit there, chilling.

958
00:51:31,380 --> 00:51:33,925
We joked about, like,
doing another Fab Five.

959
00:51:34,008 --> 00:51:35,468
At the university of Michigan.

960
00:51:36,511 --> 00:51:42,642
Myself, KG, Tractor Traylor,
Paul and Stephon.

961
00:51:43,726 --> 00:51:48,189
And when KG couldn't pass the test,
either SAT or ACT,

962
00:51:48,272 --> 00:51:50,274
he said, "Man, I'm just gonna
go to the league."

963
00:51:50,775 --> 00:51:52,318
When I heard the news
he going to the league,

964
00:51:52,401 --> 00:51:54,237
I was like, "What? You could do that?"

965
00:51:55,696 --> 00:51:57,406
He changed the game forever.

966
00:51:57,490 --> 00:52:01,118
The Minnesota Timberwolves
select Kevin Garnett…

967
00:52:01,202 --> 00:52:03,996
[Hill] A shift was occurring in '95.

968
00:52:04,080 --> 00:52:06,374
But if you shine
in the McDonald's All American Game,

969
00:52:06,457 --> 00:52:09,252
there was an immediate path to the NBA.

970
00:52:09,335 --> 00:52:12,630
Garnett was the one
that made that leap of faith,

971
00:52:12,713 --> 00:52:14,966
and that changed the game.

972
00:52:15,049 --> 00:52:19,220
What Kevin was doing at that time,
you weren't supposed to do it.

973
00:52:19,303 --> 00:52:21,138
Everyone's telling you, "Don't do it."

974
00:52:21,222 --> 00:52:25,810
So when it happened, he opened the doors.

975
00:52:25,893 --> 00:52:27,353
[crowd cheering]

976
00:52:28,855 --> 00:52:30,273
Once one guy does it, you know,

977
00:52:30,356 --> 00:52:31,941
everybody else
wants to start following suit.

978
00:52:32,024 --> 00:52:34,235
Everybody else went,
"Shit. If KG can do it, I can do it."

979
00:52:35,528 --> 00:52:38,781
[Rose] It was a crazy run
on players out of high school,

980
00:52:38,865 --> 00:52:43,119
Kobe Bryant, Jermaine O'Neal,
Tracy McGrady.

981
00:52:43,202 --> 00:52:46,664
Once these players go into the League,

982
00:52:46,747 --> 00:52:50,668
the League says,
"We wanna get better, younger."

983
00:52:52,169 --> 00:52:54,297
[commentator] Jonathan Bender,
the next contestant.

984
00:52:54,380 --> 00:52:56,257
Gonna be a terrific player
at Mississippi State.

985
00:52:56,340 --> 00:52:58,759
[commentator 2] Three-quarter court
took off the foul line!

986
00:52:58,843 --> 00:53:01,137
[Hill] So in 1999,
Jonathan Bender showed up

987
00:53:01,220 --> 00:53:05,057
at the McDonald's All American Game
and had committed to Mississippi State,

988
00:53:05,141 --> 00:53:06,309
was all set to go there,

989
00:53:06,392 --> 00:53:10,646
but something really magical
happened that evening.

990
00:53:10,730 --> 00:53:12,732
I am pleased to announce that tonight,

991
00:53:12,815 --> 00:53:17,904
Michael's All American jersey
number 23 is being retired.

992
00:53:17,987 --> 00:53:22,658
After tonight's game,
you won't see number 23 on the court.

993
00:53:22,742 --> 00:53:26,954
Michael Jordan scored 30 points,
which still stands as a record.

994
00:53:27,038 --> 00:53:30,249
[Hill] It just so happened
that MJ's Jersey was being retired.

995
00:53:30,333 --> 00:53:34,670
And as the night went on, the crowd
couldn't believe what they were seeing.

996
00:53:34,754 --> 00:53:36,213
[commentator] They're really into this.

997
00:53:36,297 --> 00:53:38,215
[commentator 2] They're on their feet.
This is amazing.

998
00:53:38,299 --> 00:53:41,761
This is a fun finish.
It's been really fun game to watch.

999
00:53:42,470 --> 00:53:44,096
-There it is!
-He did it!

1000
00:53:48,559 --> 00:53:50,394
How many people can say

1001
00:53:50,478 --> 00:53:53,522
they wiped out Air Jordan
from the record book?

1002
00:53:54,607 --> 00:53:57,068
[Hill] He broke
the all-time scoring record

1003
00:53:57,151 --> 00:54:01,530
in the McDonald's All American Game
set by the Michael Jordan.

1004
00:54:01,614 --> 00:54:05,576
And that became a launching pad
where he had options to go to the NBA,

1005
00:54:05,660 --> 00:54:06,702
which he took full advantage of.

1006
00:54:06,786 --> 00:54:10,831
Toronto Raptors select Jonathan Bender.

1007
00:54:10,915 --> 00:54:14,001
From Picayune Mississippi High School.

1008
00:54:15,002 --> 00:54:18,005
[reporter] So… So, how we feeling?
What's the mentality going into today?

1009
00:54:18,089 --> 00:54:20,591
Um, you know, just win the West. Hold up.

1010
00:54:20,675 --> 00:54:22,051
Y'all gotta get Kiki in here too.

1011
00:54:22,593 --> 00:54:25,471
-This the… This the Bruin commit.
-Yeah. UCLA.

1012
00:54:25,554 --> 00:54:28,265
So… It's, you know, only right.
Only right, you know.

1013
00:54:28,349 --> 00:54:30,434
Let's go. Head to the locker room for me.

1014
00:54:31,227 --> 00:54:32,979
[Kiki] My number one goal
over the next four years

1015
00:54:33,062 --> 00:54:35,022
is to win a national championship
and bring, you know,

1016
00:54:35,106 --> 00:54:38,401
the first, uh, national championship
to the women's side at UCLA.

1017
00:54:38,484 --> 00:54:41,821
And then, um, individually,
be a top draft pick

1018
00:54:41,904 --> 00:54:44,281
and you know to, uh,
have a great pro career,

1019
00:54:44,365 --> 00:54:47,034
championships, winning,
um, just tons of success.

1020
00:54:48,452 --> 00:54:51,247
I'm really impressed with Kiki Rice.

1021
00:54:51,330 --> 00:54:55,668
Um, she just is explosive,
uh, very versatile.

1022
00:54:55,751 --> 00:54:59,380
Also, it goes hand in hand
with, uh, Janiah Barker.

1023
00:54:59,463 --> 00:55:02,842
Uh, Janiah is very vocal,
both on and off the court.

1024
00:55:10,641 --> 00:55:12,685
-Damn, my shit blurry.
-Yeah.

1025
00:55:14,145 --> 00:55:17,857
You took one picture. Who had my phone?
Who took that picture? [chuckles]

1026
00:55:17,940 --> 00:55:19,316
-[speaks indistinctly]
-Yeah.

1027
00:55:28,534 --> 00:55:30,036
-[coach] Got it?
-Nice.

1028
00:55:30,119 --> 00:55:32,621
-Let's see it. Let's see it.
-[laughs]

1029
00:55:32,705 --> 00:55:33,706
Did you get one?

1030
00:55:34,248 --> 00:55:36,292
Um, it's on someone else's phone.

1031
00:55:36,375 --> 00:55:37,626
[chuckles] Janiah.

1032
00:55:40,379 --> 00:55:43,049
-Show me a happy girl.
-[squealing]

1033
00:55:46,927 --> 00:55:50,765
Janiah Barker is a funny, loving,
tall, goofy person.

1034
00:55:50,848 --> 00:55:53,059
Um, and of course she's a dawg.

1035
00:55:53,142 --> 00:55:57,688
[exhales deeply] Leader, competitive,
killer-mentality type of person.

1036
00:55:57,772 --> 00:56:00,357
So there's no comparison
when it comes to Janiah

1037
00:56:00,441 --> 00:56:01,734
on the court and off the court,
two different people.

1038
00:56:01,817 --> 00:56:05,071
Oh, yeah. West finna lose
and the East finna win.

1039
00:56:05,154 --> 00:56:07,073
Gonna try to get MVP.
But it's not that personal 'cause, KK,

1040
00:56:07,156 --> 00:56:09,325
-that's just my dawg. My dawg.
-You have to win to get MVP.

1041
00:56:09,408 --> 00:56:13,329
-Mmm. Mmm. [chuckles] Delusional.
-Mmm.

1042
00:56:13,412 --> 00:56:15,873
[laughing]

1043
00:56:15,956 --> 00:56:17,833
With all the awards coming out,
I got nothing.

1044
00:56:17,917 --> 00:56:21,796
I didn't get one award
like Naismith, Gatorade, anything.

1045
00:56:21,879 --> 00:56:23,631
So I really feel like
this is my chance to show people

1046
00:56:23,714 --> 00:56:25,716
that I'm gonna be number one draft pick.

1047
00:56:26,926 --> 00:56:30,763
Present day, we see the incredible play
of the women's game,

1048
00:56:30,846 --> 00:56:33,349
both in college and in the WNBA

1049
00:56:33,432 --> 00:56:36,268
and the excitement
that's generated as a result.

1050
00:56:36,936 --> 00:56:39,230
Uh, but there was a moment in time where,
you know,

1051
00:56:39,313 --> 00:56:41,899
women were fighting
for their equal footing.

1052
00:56:41,982 --> 00:56:45,986
[presenter] It was 1997 and the vision
of the WNBA was becoming a reality.

1053
00:56:46,070 --> 00:56:47,947
When the WNBA started in '97,

1054
00:56:48,030 --> 00:56:50,950
there was so much heat, like,
everybody was talking about it.

1055
00:56:51,033 --> 00:56:54,453
I mean, you had stadiums packed
to-to go watch a W game.

1056
00:56:54,537 --> 00:56:59,667
And when the Comets had their run,
it kind of ended in 2001.

1057
00:56:59,750 --> 00:57:01,836
And there wasn't as much buzz.

1058
00:57:01,919 --> 00:57:04,922
You kind of saw that drop-off a little bit
when it came to women's basketball.

1059
00:57:05,005 --> 00:57:07,174
So, like, McDonald's
kind of brought that back in.

1060
00:57:07,258 --> 00:57:09,844
It was simple.
I mean, at that time, you know,

1061
00:57:09,927 --> 00:57:13,556
it always had been about the boys.
And Bob, you know--

1062
00:57:13,639 --> 00:57:15,599
-Thinker. Idea man.
-Yeah. Thinker, just said,

1063
00:57:15,683 --> 00:57:16,934
"Hey, what about the girls?"

1064
00:57:18,310 --> 00:57:20,646
[Silver] Bob Geoghan
got pushback from corporate.

1065
00:57:21,230 --> 00:57:23,482
When you're saying, well,
"I wanna double my budget

1066
00:57:23,566 --> 00:57:26,235
because I think
there ought to be a girls' game."

1067
00:57:26,318 --> 00:57:28,362
And they say, "Wait a second,

1068
00:57:28,445 --> 00:57:30,489
you're already spending
a million and a half.

1069
00:57:30,573 --> 00:57:33,284
You wanna spend three? Why?

1070
00:57:33,367 --> 00:57:37,121
Is there enough popularity of it
to make it worth its while?"

1071
00:57:38,247 --> 00:57:42,960
I visualized in my mind
as being a great thing for the players.

1072
00:57:43,043 --> 00:57:44,962
A great thing for the fans.

1073
00:57:45,045 --> 00:57:48,090
A great thing for the charity,
and a great thing for the sponsor.

1074
00:57:48,174 --> 00:57:52,261
And so with that win-win attitude,
I said, "This is… This is pretty good."

1075
00:57:52,344 --> 00:57:56,974
My coach came in so nonchalantly
with a letter from McDonald's.

1076
00:57:57,057 --> 00:57:58,350
And I'm like, "Wait. Hold on.

1077
00:57:58,434 --> 00:58:01,187
It's got a little McDonald's logo
on there. What's going on here?"

1078
00:58:01,270 --> 00:58:04,398
And so, as I open it up, I'm reading,
"You've been," you know,

1079
00:58:05,065 --> 00:58:07,359
"invited to participate
in the McDonald's…"

1080
00:58:07,443 --> 00:58:11,405
I… Wait. They got a McDonald…
A girls' McDonald's game.

1081
00:58:11,488 --> 00:58:12,489
Like, what in the hell?

1082
00:58:12,573 --> 00:58:16,160
Now I'ma get to be a part of one,
but not understanding the magnitude

1083
00:58:16,243 --> 00:58:20,623
of, like, this is the very first one ever
for, um, the women's game.

1084
00:58:23,792 --> 00:58:27,046
[JJ Redick] We got to play our game
in Madison Square Garden.

1085
00:58:27,796 --> 00:58:31,258
Wasn't just a McDonald's game,
it was the first women's McDonald's game.

1086
00:58:31,342 --> 00:58:33,969
Obviously, we all embraced it
and thought it was awesome.

1087
00:58:34,053 --> 00:58:37,306
All of the events,
we did all of that together.

1088
00:58:38,390 --> 00:58:40,392
[Augustus] I remember it,
like, I had some cornrows.

1089
00:58:40,476 --> 00:58:42,436
It was kind of, like,
a funky little style.

1090
00:58:42,519 --> 00:58:45,773
Obviously, Melo was wearing braids
at that time too.

1091
00:58:45,856 --> 00:58:48,150
And so I remember him
giving me a compliment about it,

1092
00:58:48,234 --> 00:58:50,861
like, right as he was going into
this three-point shooting contest.

1093
00:58:50,945 --> 00:58:53,989
And then, like, Amar'e, he was
the high school kid that was coming out.

1094
00:58:54,073 --> 00:58:57,409
Everybody was hyped about him,
but he was very respectful.

1095
00:58:57,493 --> 00:58:59,745
Like, he always came over, showed love,

1096
00:58:59,828 --> 00:59:02,957
like, even after the game he was like,
"Ah, you a dawg. You was hooping."

1097
00:59:03,040 --> 00:59:05,626
Real recognize real.
And that goes for ball players too.

1098
00:59:05,709 --> 00:59:08,671
So they-they showed us a lot of love.

1099
00:59:08,754 --> 00:59:12,216
Building those friendships,
uh, last a lifetime.

1100
00:59:12,299 --> 00:59:16,887
So that was the first kind of interaction
as McDonald's All Americans

1101
00:59:16,971 --> 00:59:20,557
with the girls team and the boys team
really supporting each other

1102
00:59:20,641 --> 00:59:24,103
and loving the success
that both groups are having.

1103
00:59:25,145 --> 00:59:26,939
[crowd cheering]

1104
00:59:27,022 --> 00:59:29,817
[commentator] Augustus,
one of the two unsigned officially

1105
00:59:29,900 --> 00:59:31,777
was sensational in the first half,

1106
00:59:31,860 --> 00:59:36,532
making those who are close
very, very interested in…

1107
00:59:36,615 --> 00:59:38,325
[Augustus]
Women do have a different journey.

1108
00:59:38,409 --> 00:59:41,829
We watch these guys get drafted, you know,
they're crying, they're emotional,

1109
00:59:41,912 --> 00:59:44,331
their parents are emotional
'cause their life changed.

1110
00:59:44,415 --> 00:59:46,875
They literally hit the jackpot
like the lottery.

1111
00:59:46,959 --> 00:59:50,379
What was the… What was
the NBA rookie's salary at that moment?

1112
00:59:50,462 --> 00:59:53,424
I don't know. I had a friend,
he went first round, maybe top five pick.

1113
00:59:53,507 --> 00:59:57,344
He made four million dollars
his first year… Or five million dollars.

1114
00:59:57,428 --> 01:00:02,725
Meanwhile, we're just like, "It was great.
I fulfilled a dream or a goal."

1115
01:00:02,808 --> 01:00:06,729
But my mom and dad still had to get up
and go to work every day.

1116
01:00:06,812 --> 01:00:11,734
I still had to figure out, you know,
how to pay bills or what I had to do.

1117
01:00:11,817 --> 01:00:14,153
And it's just disheartening

1118
01:00:14,236 --> 01:00:18,615
because the pay disparity
is just so crazy here in America.

1119
01:00:18,699 --> 01:00:21,577
But yet we like, "Oh, we love… you know,
we love you.

1120
01:00:21,660 --> 01:00:26,707
We want this to work and…" Da, da, da.
But yet, the forward movement is so slow.

1121
01:00:27,291 --> 01:00:30,669
Um, when we hit the WNBA,
we took full advantage of it

1122
01:00:30,753 --> 01:00:33,547
and we tried to make sure
we was trailblazing

1123
01:00:33,630 --> 01:00:35,341
for the young ladies
that were coming behind us.

1124
01:00:35,924 --> 01:00:37,760
I think gestures like that

1125
01:00:37,843 --> 01:00:42,723
and opportunities to-to have the women
showcase like the men was long overdue,

1126
01:00:42,806 --> 01:00:46,685
but very important, I think, in the growth
and success of women's basketball.

1127
01:00:49,188 --> 01:00:52,441
I know my experience as a McDonald's
All American is one I'll never forget.

1128
01:00:53,442 --> 01:00:55,986
Just a few years ago,
I was sitting right where you are now.

1129
01:00:56,904 --> 01:00:59,615
One of the best high school
basketball players in the country,

1130
01:00:59,698 --> 01:01:02,493
getting ready to play
my first nationally televised game.

1131
01:01:03,202 --> 01:01:06,080
Like you, I was dreaming
of a career in the NBA.

1132
01:01:06,163 --> 01:01:08,749
You know, I was in the same situation
as you guys. They had

1133
01:01:08,832 --> 01:01:12,252
Michael Jordan, uh,
come on the TV and talk to us.

1134
01:01:12,336 --> 01:01:17,591
And, you know, even though
that's, uh… that's Mike, we're like,

1135
01:01:17,674 --> 01:01:19,968
"All right, man. Stop talking.
You're talking too much."

1136
01:01:20,052 --> 01:01:21,887
So I'm not gonna do thesame thing
to you guys.

1137
01:01:21,970 --> 01:01:24,848
I'm gonna let you guys go ahead,
have a good time this week.

1138
01:01:24,932 --> 01:01:28,143
Enjoy yourselves. And I'll be waiting
for you guys in the NBA.

1139
01:01:30,229 --> 01:01:34,233
[JJ Redick] In June of 2001, a group of us
played in Colorado Springs

1140
01:01:34,316 --> 01:01:35,776
at the USA Basketball Development Camp.

1141
01:01:35,859 --> 01:01:41,323
We're in the dorms and Sean Dockery,
who's from Chicago, went to Duke with me.

1142
01:01:41,407 --> 01:01:43,826
He said, "I'm gonna go back
and I'm gonna tell all my friends

1143
01:01:43,909 --> 01:01:46,537
I just saw the best basketball player
I've ever seen."

1144
01:01:46,620 --> 01:01:49,498
He was talking about LeBron,
and LeBron was 15 at the time.

1145
01:01:49,581 --> 01:01:51,375
[presenter]
With a Sports Illustrated cover,

1146
01:01:51,458 --> 01:01:53,669
-sold-out games from coast to coast…
-[crowd cheering]

1147
01:01:53,752 --> 01:01:57,589
…a pay-per-view audience,
LeBron James is everywhere.

1148
01:01:57,673 --> 01:02:01,927
Even David Letterman has to stand in line.
This kid is hot.

1149
01:02:02,010 --> 01:02:04,263
-[whistle blows]
-[cheering]

1150
01:02:04,346 --> 01:02:07,433
It's LeBron James
who's got sneaker companies

1151
01:02:07,516 --> 01:02:12,354
fighting to offer him a deal
worth 20 to 30 million dollars.

1152
01:02:12,438 --> 01:02:15,983
And that's before the kid
even attends his own prom.

1153
01:02:16,066 --> 01:02:19,445
You know, I just look at it as
this opportunity for me and my teammates.

1154
01:02:19,528 --> 01:02:23,031
You know, every time I go out there,
they also gotta see my teammates also.

1155
01:02:23,115 --> 01:02:26,618
So, I'm a team-first, me-second
type of player.

1156
01:02:26,702 --> 01:02:31,206
Before LeBron James, high school
basketball really wasn't on TV.

1157
01:02:31,290 --> 01:02:34,793
The hype, the exposure
was at an all-time high.

1158
01:02:34,877 --> 01:02:37,004
His reputation preceded him.

1159
01:02:37,087 --> 01:02:40,674
And therefore,
it was a media frenzy in Cleveland.

1160
01:02:42,050 --> 01:02:45,304
Can you talk about this experience?
Everything you did in the last few games.

1161
01:02:46,346 --> 01:02:47,431
Uh…

1162
01:02:48,056 --> 01:02:49,433
[JJ Redick] He was so grounded.

1163
01:02:50,225 --> 01:02:54,438
Despite all of the hype,
he was still a kid from Akron.

1164
01:02:54,521 --> 01:02:56,690
[Hill] Now, it was like center stage,

1165
01:02:56,773 --> 01:03:00,986
felt like a major event was occurring
with LeBron James,

1166
01:03:01,069 --> 01:03:03,822
uh, you know, in the 2003
McDonald's All American Game.

1167
01:03:03,906 --> 01:03:07,659
And everyone from Dick Vitale
to the Hamburglar and Ronald himself

1168
01:03:07,743 --> 01:03:09,286
knew that LeBron James would wind up

1169
01:03:09,369 --> 01:03:12,164
in tonight's McDonald's
High School All American Game.

1170
01:03:12,247 --> 01:03:14,791
After all, the event took place
in Cleveland, Ohio,

1171
01:03:14,875 --> 01:03:17,419
a quick 45-minute Humvee ride away

1172
01:03:17,503 --> 01:03:21,715
for King James to make undoubtedly
the final amateur appearance of his life.

1173
01:03:21,798 --> 01:03:23,258
Guns Arena here in Cleveland, Ohio,

1174
01:03:23,342 --> 01:03:28,805
the site of the 26th annual McDonald's
Boys High School All American Game.

1175
01:03:28,889 --> 01:03:31,225
And this one, of course,
figures to be very special.

1176
01:03:31,308 --> 01:03:34,603
LeBron James against the rest
of the All Americans here tonight.

1177
01:03:34,686 --> 01:03:38,232
You've seen him dominate so many times.
Can he dominate against players this good?

1178
01:03:38,315 --> 01:03:40,901
[commentator]
Guys, is-is it sacrilege to point out

1179
01:03:40,984 --> 01:03:43,445
that maybe he's overrated at this point?

1180
01:03:43,529 --> 01:03:47,491
He's compared to the greatest of all time.
Is it a fair question to ask?

1181
01:03:47,574 --> 01:03:49,826
[commentator 2] His players start off
on the defensive end.

1182
01:03:49,910 --> 01:03:50,911
[crowd cheering]

1183
01:03:50,994 --> 01:03:54,873
Chris Paul to LeBron James.
That didn't take very long.

1184
01:03:54,957 --> 01:03:56,792
Points up to them
on his way back down the floor.

1185
01:03:56,875 --> 01:03:59,753
And now he's gotta steal,
unselfishly gives it up

1186
01:03:59,836 --> 01:04:01,964
and Michael Jones will finish with James.

1187
01:04:02,047 --> 01:04:03,966
[reporter] You look like you're
having a lot of fun,

1188
01:04:04,049 --> 01:04:05,551
but I thought you'd try
to dunk everything.

1189
01:04:05,634 --> 01:04:08,512
You're trying to get your teammates
involved. Take me through your mindset.

1190
01:04:08,595 --> 01:04:11,682
[LeBron] You know, when your teammates get
into it, we have a lot more fun out there.

1191
01:04:11,765 --> 01:04:14,268
Trying to not be selfish.
We're just trying to play a team game.

1192
01:04:14,351 --> 01:04:15,852
Thankful that we up by 12 right now.

1193
01:04:20,524 --> 01:04:24,236
[commentator] Time out on the floor.
LeBron James's moment right here.

1194
01:04:24,319 --> 01:04:27,531
Just up the road from Akron.
The fans loving the show.

1195
01:04:27,614 --> 01:04:32,869
Here's Coach Wootten with the presentation
of the trophy to LeBron James.

1196
01:04:32,953 --> 01:04:35,038
[announcer] LeBron James!

1197
01:04:36,498 --> 01:04:38,000
[speaks indistinctly]

1198
01:04:39,126 --> 01:04:41,169
[commentator] If you had
never heard of any of these players

1199
01:04:41,253 --> 01:04:43,589
and you came in here to watch the game,
would you walk out saying

1200
01:04:43,672 --> 01:04:46,091
-he was the best player on the floor?
-Oh, without question.

1201
01:04:46,174 --> 01:04:48,260
You know, this night was about
LeBron James.

1202
01:04:48,343 --> 01:04:51,221
I came in a little bit skeptical.
I saw him practice last year.

1203
01:04:51,305 --> 01:04:53,724
I saw both of his games on ESPN this year.

1204
01:04:53,807 --> 01:04:56,351
He is as good as advertised
and he's very explosive.

1205
01:04:56,435 --> 01:04:58,770
You see what LeBron was able to do
in playing that McDonald's game,

1206
01:04:58,854 --> 01:05:02,107
rocking the 32 jersey,
paying homage to Magic,

1207
01:05:02,190 --> 01:05:04,860
and only time we got to see LeBron
in a dunk contest.

1208
01:05:05,444 --> 01:05:08,864
[commentator] The man is ready.
This is why we're here.

1209
01:05:08,947 --> 01:05:11,700
Yeah, I'm-I'm afraid
he may jump out of his britches.

1210
01:05:12,451 --> 01:05:13,994
That's gonna take a long run-up.

1211
01:05:15,829 --> 01:05:17,706
Oh, my goodness!

1212
01:05:18,332 --> 01:05:22,794
-That was the first one? Wow.
-[laughs]

1213
01:05:22,878 --> 01:05:24,713
Are you k… Oh.

1214
01:05:27,924 --> 01:05:29,384
[Josiah] To see LeBron
in that dunk contest,

1215
01:05:29,468 --> 01:05:32,262
how big he was and just how much
of a grown-ass man he was.

1216
01:05:32,346 --> 01:05:34,014
Wish he would have did in the NBA as well.

1217
01:05:34,097 --> 01:05:36,642
But now you can go back
and that-that memory lives on forever.

1218
01:05:37,643 --> 01:05:40,187
Beautiful delivery of the ball.
Oh, my God.

1219
01:05:40,270 --> 01:05:42,105
[commentators laugh]

1220
01:05:43,523 --> 01:05:46,652
A year ago in the McDonald's High School
All American Game party,

1221
01:05:46,735 --> 01:05:47,736
one word, LeBron.

1222
01:05:47,819 --> 01:05:50,906
High School equivalent of Glory
won the Slam Dunk Contest,

1223
01:05:50,989 --> 01:05:52,449
then took the MVP in the game.

1224
01:05:52,532 --> 01:05:56,244
This year's Slam Dunk winner will not win
the game MVP 'cause she's not playing.

1225
01:05:56,328 --> 01:05:57,704
Yeah. She.

1226
01:05:58,622 --> 01:06:00,791
-Dudes lost to a girl.
-[scoffs]

1227
01:06:00,874 --> 01:06:04,461
Tonight's events include
a co-ed Slam Dunk Contest.

1228
01:06:04,544 --> 01:06:07,923
Carmelo Anthony knows about dunks.
Would you have ever let a girl

1229
01:06:08,006 --> 01:06:09,549
-beat you in a dunk contest?
-No, I wouldn't.

1230
01:06:09,633 --> 01:06:13,595
[commentator]
Candace Parker, who is off to Tennessee…

1231
01:06:13,679 --> 01:06:16,139
-She covers her eyes!
-She did it blindfolded!

1232
01:06:17,516 --> 01:06:20,185
Tens around.
We have history, ladies and gentlemen,

1233
01:06:20,268 --> 01:06:24,272
here in Oklahoma City.
Candace Parker, your winner.

1234
01:06:24,356 --> 01:06:26,900
[Parker] My brother
was playing overseas at the time.

1235
01:06:26,983 --> 01:06:29,111
So he was just like,
"How did everything go?"

1236
01:06:30,112 --> 01:06:34,032
And I remember being like, "Well, I won."

1237
01:06:34,116 --> 01:06:36,576
He hung up that call not believing me.

1238
01:06:36,660 --> 01:06:39,746
[commentator] Tonight, we'll see
which future star can live up to the hype…

1239
01:06:39,830 --> 01:06:40,831
[screams]

1240
01:06:40,914 --> 01:06:43,625
…as the greatest high school players
take the floor…

1241
01:06:43,709 --> 01:06:44,710
Sup, y'all?

1242
01:06:44,793 --> 01:06:47,254
…in the 27th annual McDonald's
All American High School Game.

1243
01:06:47,963 --> 01:06:51,174
[Hill] There was a sense
that things would change.

1244
01:06:51,258 --> 01:06:54,636
That the NBA,
along with the Players Association

1245
01:06:54,720 --> 01:06:59,307
would eliminate high school players
jumping right to the NBA.

1246
01:06:59,391 --> 01:07:04,104
And so for the next year or two
at the McDonald's All American Game,

1247
01:07:04,187 --> 01:07:08,108
all the scouts were there
because they knew that this might be it.

1248
01:07:08,191 --> 01:07:11,236
And there was uncertainty
as to what it would look like

1249
01:07:11,319 --> 01:07:13,029
going forward in the future.

1250
01:07:13,613 --> 01:07:16,825
Tim, more NBA scouts watching this game
maybe than ever before.

1251
01:07:16,908 --> 01:07:18,744
Yeah, Dave.
And I think this has the potential

1252
01:07:18,827 --> 01:07:23,915
to be the most competitive McDonald's
All-Star Game in their 27-year history.

1253
01:07:23,999 --> 01:07:27,878
All 29 NBA teams are represented
here in Oklahoma City.

1254
01:07:27,961 --> 01:07:31,715
Nine of the boys are considering
a jump directly to the NBA,

1255
01:07:31,798 --> 01:07:33,717
depending on their All-Star performances.

1256
01:07:33,800 --> 01:07:37,053
[commentator] The work ethic
is amazing among these players as--

1257
01:07:37,137 --> 01:07:40,432
-And Nelson gets stopped by Josh Smith!
-[commentator 21] Whoa.

1258
01:07:40,515 --> 01:07:42,517
-What a block.
-Incredible elevation.

1259
01:07:42,601 --> 01:07:45,312
My goodness.
Remember, Doug, I told you earlier

1260
01:07:45,395 --> 01:07:48,231
that these guys are trying
to impress the scouts.

1261
01:07:48,315 --> 01:07:52,694
Draft status is at stake.
This is not your normal All-Star Game.

1262
01:07:52,778 --> 01:07:54,571
Athletic moves like we see from Josh Smith

1263
01:07:54,654 --> 01:07:57,032
will earn them a higher draft stock.

1264
01:07:57,115 --> 01:08:00,786
Washington to Smith! Oh!

1265
01:08:00,869 --> 01:08:03,914
Josh Smith on both ends of the floor!

1266
01:08:03,997 --> 01:08:07,667
JR Smith continues to impress.
Boy, I… I'm Roy Williams,

1267
01:08:07,751 --> 01:08:09,127
I'm turning off the TV as well.

1268
01:08:09,211 --> 01:08:13,590
It'll be a long night in Chapel Hill after
watching the McDonalds's All American Game

1269
01:08:13,673 --> 01:08:14,966
whether he'll attend college.

1270
01:08:15,050 --> 01:08:17,344
Dwight, you get
that first big paycheck next fall.

1271
01:08:17,426 --> 01:08:19,136
What's the first thing
that you're gonna buy?

1272
01:08:19,220 --> 01:08:22,015
I'm gonna buy my mom and dad a nice car.

1273
01:08:22,098 --> 01:08:24,434
All right. Very good.
Get back there and have fun.

1274
01:08:24,518 --> 01:08:27,229
And, Dave, he's going to make
his official announcement

1275
01:08:27,312 --> 01:08:29,689
on April 12th about the NBA.

1276
01:08:29,773 --> 01:08:32,776
[commentator] Sebastian Telfair.
Should he stay or should he to go the NBA?

1277
01:08:32,859 --> 01:08:34,736
Well, I think we both agree
he should stay.

1278
01:08:34,819 --> 01:08:37,197
But if the opportunity is there
to be a first-round pick

1279
01:08:37,279 --> 01:08:41,660
a-and you can take your family
out of a very difficult area in the Bronx,

1280
01:08:41,743 --> 01:08:42,828
he probably has to go.

1281
01:08:42,911 --> 01:08:46,413
You did exactly what you had to do.
You did exactly what you had to do, man.

1282
01:08:46,497 --> 01:08:48,707
You're a forward general.
That was fantastic.

1283
01:08:48,792 --> 01:08:50,919
You didn't have to score
in a game like this.

1284
01:08:51,002 --> 01:08:52,629
That's what everyone was looking for,
Sebastian.

1285
01:08:52,712 --> 01:08:54,089
-I'm so proud of you.
-Thank you.

1286
01:08:54,171 --> 01:08:57,175
-[clamoring]
-Thank you.

1287
01:08:59,636 --> 01:09:00,679
I'll see y'all, man.

1288
01:09:02,389 --> 01:09:03,473
Tremendous.

1289
01:09:03,557 --> 01:09:07,978
Because you didn't try to do anything
except what you're supposed to do.

1290
01:09:08,060 --> 01:09:14,192
This is when the team played the way
a true league-aligned is supposed to play.

1291
01:09:14,276 --> 01:09:16,778
Nobody does that, except for…

1292
01:09:16,862 --> 01:09:18,529
-Thanks a lot. Thanks.
-'Cause you're a pro.

1293
01:09:18,613 --> 01:09:20,198
-[laughs] Oh, yeah? I am?
-Yes, you are.

1294
01:09:20,282 --> 01:09:21,283
I hope so.

1295
01:09:21,366 --> 01:09:23,785
Uh, David Stern,
the commissioner of the NBA,

1296
01:09:23,868 --> 01:09:25,996
weighed in on this issue.
And here's what he had to say.

1297
01:09:26,078 --> 01:09:29,165
He said that
"We would love to add a year…"

1298
01:09:29,249 --> 01:09:31,877
Meaning that players would
have to wait two before they come in.

1299
01:09:31,960 --> 01:09:35,046
"But that's not something the Players'
Association has been willing to agree to.

1300
01:09:35,130 --> 01:09:39,426
Our rule is that they won't be eligible
for the draft until they're 19."

1301
01:09:40,010 --> 01:09:44,805
2006, the NBA Players Association
implemented the one-and-done rule.

1302
01:09:44,890 --> 01:09:46,308
Players had to go to college

1303
01:09:46,390 --> 01:09:50,812
or at least be one year removed
from their high school graduating class.

1304
01:09:51,354 --> 01:09:54,900
Uh, so all of a sudden, you know,
the stakes aren't as high.

1305
01:09:56,610 --> 01:10:00,155
Even with that change,
it still meant something.

1306
01:10:00,238 --> 01:10:05,035
It still was checking a box
of what your goal might be

1307
01:10:05,118 --> 01:10:07,412
when you're young and achieving that goal.

1308
01:10:07,495 --> 01:10:12,500
It's still something that brings
great pride for these men and women.

1309
01:10:12,584 --> 01:10:15,462
To be honored. To be in the game.
To be chosen.

1310
01:10:16,004 --> 01:10:17,130
♪ Dream ♪

1311
01:10:18,006 --> 01:10:21,217
♪ Dream like the wind
Free and unbounded ♪

1312
01:10:22,344 --> 01:10:25,639
♪ Dream like the river
Flowing without end ♪

1313
01:10:26,973 --> 01:10:30,310
♪ Dream like fire
Burning with passion ♪

1314
01:10:31,144 --> 01:10:35,815
♪ Dream like a tree, rooted
Yet reaching toward the sun ♪

1315
01:10:36,942 --> 01:10:40,278
♪ Dream high, dream wide, dream bold ♪

1316
01:10:40,362 --> 01:10:43,740
♪ Dream fearless, dream passionate
Dream persistent ♪

1317
01:10:45,951 --> 01:10:52,582
♪ Dream like God's love
Patient, kind, not envious or boastful ♪

1318
01:10:53,458 --> 01:10:56,002
♪ Keep on dreaming, man ♪

1319
01:10:56,086 --> 01:10:59,756
♪ Dream like a journey
The sweat, the tears ♪

1320
01:11:00,590 --> 01:11:03,760
♪ Dream for legacy beyond your years ♪

1321
01:11:04,427 --> 01:11:06,554
♪ Dream, man,
Dream ♪

1322
01:11:07,138 --> 01:11:09,307
When I first got announced
to be a McDonald's All American,

1323
01:11:09,391 --> 01:11:10,892
it was like a dream come true.

1324
01:11:10,976 --> 01:11:14,604
Uh, I watched the game when I was younger.
Just, like, dreaming to play in that game.

1325
01:11:14,688 --> 01:11:17,983
So, to actually finally be named…
To be a McDonald's All American,

1326
01:11:18,066 --> 01:11:19,275
it means everything to me.

1327
01:11:20,610 --> 01:11:23,113
[Flau'jae] Never let nobody
dictate your dreams.

1328
01:11:23,196 --> 01:11:25,490
Never let nobody put fear
inside your dreams

1329
01:11:25,573 --> 01:11:27,075
'cause they can't see your dreams.

1330
01:11:27,158 --> 01:11:29,244
God didn't give 'em to them.
They gave 'em to you.

1331
01:11:29,869 --> 01:11:32,914
So, don't ever give up on your dream
because of what somebody else says.

1332
01:11:33,498 --> 01:11:36,626
I missed my prom. The prom, March 26th.

1333
01:11:37,210 --> 01:11:40,964
McDonald's All American,
the 25th through the 30th.

1334
01:11:41,047 --> 01:11:43,675
I did wanna go out in my little dress
with my… with my…

1335
01:11:43,758 --> 01:11:47,220
[stammers] my slick…
my slick, um, red lace and my heels.

1336
01:11:47,303 --> 01:11:51,808
But it's okay. I-I might just get my dress
and take some pictures when we get back.

1337
01:11:51,891 --> 01:11:55,603
Just to take the pictures, not…
But I did miss prom. That's crazy.

1338
01:11:56,229 --> 01:11:58,231
[sighs] It's definitely gonna be worth it.

1339
01:11:58,314 --> 01:12:01,443
Depending on what I do in that game
tomorrow, it's gonna make it all worth it.

1340
01:12:02,110 --> 01:12:06,573
Lip bust right here.
Pinkie messed up, swollen.

1341
01:12:07,866 --> 01:12:10,618
Ah. It just pop. It's swollen.

1342
01:12:10,702 --> 01:12:14,581
My lip, my… my finger might be broke.

1343
01:12:14,664 --> 01:12:16,583
But you know, it just come with the game.

1344
01:12:16,666 --> 01:12:20,336
I don't complain.
Like, some people that use that excuse.

1345
01:12:20,420 --> 01:12:22,464
"My pinkie broke, I'm not…" Nah, bruh.

1346
01:12:22,547 --> 01:12:26,051
I finna be like, my pinkie broke
and I'm still finna win MVP. Feel me?

1347
01:12:31,765 --> 01:12:35,101
[Barker] I… I came from nothing.
I came from nothing,

1348
01:12:35,185 --> 01:12:38,480
so when I see where I'm at, right…
When I look where I'm at,

1349
01:12:38,563 --> 01:12:40,774
I'm grateful to have people around me
and… and…

1350
01:12:41,941 --> 01:12:44,861
It's crazy,
so to even be in this position… [huffs]

1351
01:12:55,038 --> 01:12:56,039
[sniffles]

1352
01:12:58,750 --> 01:13:01,002
[inhales sharply, exhales heavily]
Sorry. [breathes shakily]

1353
01:13:02,337 --> 01:13:04,214
I really owe it all to my parents and…

1354
01:13:04,297 --> 01:13:06,758
[sniffles] My coaches.

1355
01:13:06,841 --> 01:13:09,969
My family moved for basketball.
They… They literally m…

1356
01:13:10,053 --> 01:13:13,681
Picked up everything they had,
moved from a house to… to a apartment.

1357
01:13:14,390 --> 01:13:16,893
Share… I share a room with my brother
when I first got there.

1358
01:13:16,976 --> 01:13:18,770
It was my first time
sharing a room with him.

1359
01:13:18,853 --> 01:13:21,064
But he made the sacrifice too.

1360
01:13:21,147 --> 01:13:24,400
You know… You know when you talk to God
and you question him… [sniffles]

1361
01:13:24,484 --> 01:13:26,027
You wonder why.

1362
01:13:26,111 --> 01:13:29,489
But then things like this happen
and he shows you

1363
01:13:29,572 --> 01:13:31,783
why he put you through
what you… what you went through.

1364
01:13:32,867 --> 01:13:35,286
Yeah. I know what it's like
to have nothing… So…

1365
01:13:35,370 --> 01:13:37,622
To have all of this is a blessing.

1366
01:13:41,417 --> 01:13:44,963
This my meal ticket
and I gotta… I gotta use it.

1367
01:13:46,673 --> 01:13:47,799
[people chattering]

1368
01:13:49,676 --> 01:13:50,677
[speaks indistinctly]

1369
01:13:54,055 --> 01:13:57,767
-[players cheering]
-Let's go. Let's go.

1370
01:13:57,851 --> 01:13:59,894
-Ay, East on three. One, two, three. East.
-[all] East.

1371
01:13:59,978 --> 01:14:04,399
Kiki, Flau'jae, Chance, Ruby, Justine,

1372
01:14:04,482 --> 01:14:07,443
Raegan, Ayanna, Lauren, Janiah. Good.

1373
01:14:07,527 --> 01:14:10,405
[players cheering, whooping]

1374
01:14:11,114 --> 01:14:14,909
To see the history and the culture
behind what it meant to…

1375
01:14:14,993 --> 01:14:17,579
to be a McDonald's All American,
and then to be a part of that,

1376
01:14:17,662 --> 01:14:20,165
my parents were more than proud.

1377
01:14:20,707 --> 01:14:27,589
[Greg G The Goldenchild]
♪ And the rockets' red glare ♪

1378
01:14:27,672 --> 01:14:29,299
♪ The bombs bursting… ♪

1379
01:14:29,382 --> 01:14:33,887
[Augustus] I feel thankful
and grateful that I got that letter

1380
01:14:33,970 --> 01:14:36,472
that basically invited me
to be a part of something

1381
01:14:36,556 --> 01:14:40,518
that's now gonna have a history
that lives on forever.

1382
01:14:40,602 --> 01:14:44,105
♪ That our flag was still there ♪

1383
01:14:44,189 --> 01:14:46,983
When I saw my name on ESPN…
I remember watching it with my parents.

1384
01:14:47,066 --> 01:14:49,277
I never would have imagined that
my name would be listed

1385
01:14:49,360 --> 01:14:51,279
with a lot of great players
across the nation.

1386
01:14:51,362 --> 01:14:57,035
♪ …star-spangled banner yet wave ♪

1387
01:14:57,118 --> 01:14:59,746
[Parker] Provide a game
and we will put on a show.

1388
01:14:59,829 --> 01:15:02,415
Provide a platform,
and we'll take advantage of it.

1389
01:15:02,498 --> 01:15:04,959
Put us on TV and people will watch.

1390
01:15:05,793 --> 01:15:09,255
[Borzello] The most star-studded
night in high school basketball is back.

1391
01:15:09,339 --> 01:15:14,844
One of those standouts, Flau'jae Johnson.
A star on the court and on the mic.

1392
01:15:16,304 --> 01:15:18,264
[commentator] So far,
exactly what we expected to see.

1393
01:15:18,348 --> 01:15:23,102
Some quick, fast-paced talent.
Strong block by Ayanna Patterson.

1394
01:15:24,270 --> 01:15:25,313
Let's go, Flau!

1395
01:15:25,396 --> 01:15:27,023
Barker's been active in this game already.

1396
01:15:27,106 --> 01:15:28,483
-[Borzello] It's 2-1.
-Ooh!

1397
01:15:28,566 --> 01:15:31,736
[Borzello] And Barker finishes herself.
She's got all six.

1398
01:15:32,278 --> 01:15:37,325
And Ashlyn Watkins run at Rice.
Puts it in. Plus the foul.

1399
01:15:40,578 --> 01:15:46,000
Seven to shoot. Johnson. Over Rice.
Johnson on the try. East ball.

1400
01:15:49,420 --> 01:15:52,298
It's the West with love to give.
Flau'jae Johnson going.

1401
01:15:52,382 --> 01:15:54,259
She's 0 of seven with two points.

1402
01:15:54,342 --> 01:15:58,137
There's Flau'jae Johnson.
Her first shot right from the floor.

1403
01:16:05,937 --> 01:16:08,147
Now, Rice against Jaquez again.

1404
01:16:08,231 --> 01:16:11,985
Oh. Rice knifing through.

1405
01:16:12,068 --> 01:16:15,989
-[horn blows]
-And that does it. Here in Chicago,

1406
01:16:16,072 --> 01:16:20,159
the East triumphs over the West.
Our two MVPs are with Brooke.

1407
01:16:20,243 --> 01:16:22,078
How did this game feel in your mind?

1408
01:16:22,161 --> 01:16:24,998
We just focus on defensive intensity
and, you know, we came out hard.

1409
01:16:25,081 --> 01:16:27,458
We, uh, we were really focusing on
just, you know,

1410
01:16:27,542 --> 01:16:30,211
having a good start and playing our game.
And I think we executed the game plan.

1411
01:16:30,295 --> 01:16:31,963
[cheering]

1412
01:16:56,904 --> 01:16:58,865
[indistinct chatter]

1413
01:17:03,202 --> 01:17:05,079
Good job.

1414
01:17:06,789 --> 01:17:10,418
Proud of you. Flau'jae, stop it.

1415
01:17:11,085 --> 01:17:13,755
-You be beating yourself up, man. I know.
-No.

1416
01:17:13,838 --> 01:17:18,926
I know it's a mentality thing, but, baby,
that's a all-star game with all all-stars.

1417
01:17:19,552 --> 01:17:21,929
-Everybody had to play…
-Nah. But it's my… [stammers]

1418
01:17:22,013 --> 01:17:26,267
I know your hand. But you… you scored
15 points with a broke fractured finger.

1419
01:17:26,893 --> 01:17:28,603
In the little bit of time
that you've been in there,

1420
01:17:28,686 --> 01:17:30,438
you killing yourself for no reason.

1421
01:17:31,147 --> 01:17:34,067
I know but I just… I don't know.
I expected more.

1422
01:17:34,150 --> 01:17:37,320
I know. But this… this different.
It's supposed to just be fun.

1423
01:17:37,403 --> 01:17:39,447
Everybody just supposed to be
showing their talent.

1424
01:17:39,530 --> 01:17:41,282
You know what I'm saying?
Ain't supposed to be like,

1425
01:17:41,366 --> 01:17:44,285
"Oh, you gotta score 40."
Like, that's crazy.

1426
01:17:44,369 --> 01:17:46,704
You know what I'm saying?
It ain't like that. You killed it.

1427
01:17:47,413 --> 01:17:48,831
-You killed it.
-Ow.

1428
01:17:48,915 --> 01:17:50,541
Oh, I forgot. Oh, sorry.

1429
01:17:51,959 --> 01:17:53,878
I'm mad that I didn't get that MVP.

1430
01:17:53,961 --> 01:17:57,924
But at the same time, it's like, I mean,
I'm a McDonald's All American. Like…

1431
01:17:58,007 --> 01:17:59,801
I was… I was on TV.
You know what I'm saying, like…

1432
01:17:59,884 --> 01:18:03,012
Thank you, girl. I need you…
I need you to stop beating yourself up.

1433
01:18:03,096 --> 01:18:05,515
-Yeah.
-Baby, you are a great. You get me?

1434
01:18:05,598 --> 01:18:07,433
-Do you hear me, girl?
-Yeah.

1435
01:18:07,517 --> 01:18:08,559
Okay. [kisses]

1436
01:18:08,643 --> 01:18:10,812
-But I don't feel down no more, man.
-Please.

1437
01:18:10,895 --> 01:18:12,105
I-I… [scoffs]

1438
01:18:13,231 --> 01:18:14,690
I'm coming back for vengeance.
Just know that.

1439
01:18:14,774 --> 01:18:17,110
Next time I'm on ESPN,
y'all gone feel me. On God.

1440
01:18:26,035 --> 01:18:28,663
[Joe] People see 'em
as these great NBA players.

1441
01:18:29,330 --> 01:18:31,165
When they're at the McDonald's Game,
they're just kids.

1442
01:18:31,249 --> 01:18:34,043
They wanna be treated for who they are
as people, not necessarily as players.

1443
01:18:36,504 --> 01:18:39,799
I consider it a sacred trust. Um…

1444
01:18:41,843 --> 01:18:44,554
You know, because… Let me say why.
Because…

1445
01:18:44,637 --> 01:18:46,806
'Cause, you know, it's about…
It's not about the right…

1446
01:18:46,889 --> 01:18:47,890
Which shoe they wear.

1447
01:18:47,974 --> 01:18:49,892
It's not about where they go to school.
It's not…

1448
01:18:49,976 --> 01:18:54,021
It's about the 24 best boys,
the 24 best girls.

1449
01:18:54,105 --> 01:18:57,608
It's, you know, why we do it.
It's the legacy of our family.

1450
01:18:57,692 --> 01:18:59,861
And just everything that Morgan expected.

1451
01:19:06,742 --> 01:19:10,371
[Silver] For a game to be 47 years…

1452
01:19:11,038 --> 01:19:14,542
A high school game to be 47 years old,

1453
01:19:15,501 --> 01:19:18,921
that to me is a legacy of Bob Geoghan.

1454
01:19:19,005 --> 01:19:22,300
[announcer] At this time,
we ask for a brief moment of silence

1455
01:19:22,383 --> 01:19:24,343
in honor of Bob Geoghan.

1456
01:19:26,929 --> 01:19:30,141
He was the kind of person
that was behind the scenes always.

1457
01:19:30,224 --> 01:19:36,439
Did not make any money,
which I regret honestly.

1458
01:19:37,273 --> 01:19:40,067
That something as special as this
has become,

1459
01:19:41,068 --> 01:19:43,696
and for him to be, um…

1460
01:19:45,907 --> 01:19:49,911
to be broke when he passed away…
had no money…

1461
01:19:50,495 --> 01:19:53,206
That hurt. That really hurt.

1462
01:19:55,416 --> 01:19:59,837
But the legacy of the game transcends him.

1463
01:20:01,923 --> 01:20:04,967
So… that's special.

1464
01:20:06,511 --> 01:20:09,805
What makes basketball great in this area.
Here he is. Bob Geoghan.

1465
01:20:09,889 --> 01:20:12,558
For the seventh year,
another tremendous, tremendous event

1466
01:20:12,642 --> 01:20:13,893
here in the capital center.

1467
01:20:13,976 --> 01:20:16,312
Well, thank you very much, Mal.
We're certainly proud of it

1468
01:20:16,395 --> 01:20:19,524
and, uh, as long as fans
keep supporting it like they do,

1469
01:20:19,607 --> 01:20:21,150
there's no question in my mind that, uh,

1470
01:20:21,234 --> 01:20:23,444
it'll continue to be the number one game
in the country.

1471
01:20:24,904 --> 01:20:30,743
"Sonny, I met you for the first time
in 1973 when you came to DC

1472
01:20:30,826 --> 01:20:35,498
and had a meeting with me across from
Lefty Jezel's restaurant in College Park

1473
01:20:35,581 --> 01:20:38,709
to discuss my creating
the McDonald's Capital Classic.

1474
01:20:39,377 --> 01:20:41,796
I wanted to say I always admired you.

1475
01:20:41,879 --> 01:20:46,676
Although, at times we competed for some of
the same players for our all-star games.

1476
01:20:47,510 --> 01:20:50,930
I had a stroke last August
and I'm still in rehab.

1477
01:20:51,013 --> 01:20:52,723
So, I'm retiring for good.

1478
01:20:53,432 --> 01:20:57,562
Godspeed, my friend,
as we approach the end of our lives.

1479
01:20:58,271 --> 01:21:00,106
Thanks, Sonny, for the memories.

1480
01:21:02,275 --> 01:21:03,359
Bob Geoghan."

1481
01:21:12,994 --> 01:21:14,328
[crowd cheering]

1482
01:21:15,663 --> 01:21:19,000
Hello. You doing okay?
Good to see you. Man, listen--

1483
01:21:19,083 --> 01:21:22,878
-[mumbles] Man, I just asked was you here.
-I know. He was just telling me right now.

1484
01:21:22,962 --> 01:21:25,214
Right, man, I'm gonna say
that I have my young 'un…

1485
01:21:25,298 --> 01:21:27,550
I think the McDonald's Game
propelled my career

1486
01:21:27,633 --> 01:21:31,137
because i-it gave me opportunity
to put my name on the big stage.

1487
01:21:31,220 --> 01:21:34,640
Especially back then. Yeah, we wasn't
playing on ESPN every single weekend

1488
01:21:34,724 --> 01:21:37,393
so, you know, it took the game,
the McDonald's All American Game,

1489
01:21:37,476 --> 01:21:41,355
to really, uh, kinda ignite our names
and take it to the next level.

1490
01:21:41,439 --> 01:21:45,985
[Borzello] There is no bigger stage
than the McDonald's All American Game.

1491
01:21:46,068 --> 01:21:49,155
Knowing that the majority of guys
that make the McDonald's All American Game

1492
01:21:49,238 --> 01:21:50,615
go on to play professionally,

1493
01:21:50,698 --> 01:21:51,866
that's a pretty crazy stat.

1494
01:21:51,949 --> 01:21:55,494
I don't know how many other games
there are like that

1495
01:21:55,578 --> 01:21:57,705
where the success rate is so high.

1496
01:21:58,831 --> 01:22:00,708
It just puts you on this path

1497
01:22:00,791 --> 01:22:04,211
and you just gotta do everything you can
to keep going forward.

1498
01:22:04,295 --> 01:22:07,423
[commentator]
Dereck Lively II going to Duke.

1499
01:22:07,506 --> 01:22:11,344
It was something as a kid
that I wanted to be a part of.

1500
01:22:11,427 --> 01:22:14,055
High school basketball,
you wanna be a McDonald's All American.

1501
01:22:14,138 --> 01:22:15,931
Like, that is the elite of the elite.

1502
01:22:18,017 --> 01:22:21,354
\It was like one of those things
where I wanted to collect everything

1503
01:22:21,437 --> 01:22:24,231
and I was top.
They said you was top of your class.

1504
01:22:24,315 --> 01:22:26,400
I had to be a McDonald's All American.

1505
01:22:26,484 --> 01:22:28,069
[Borzello] Off we go. 20-minute halves.

1506
01:22:28,152 --> 01:22:32,865
And Amari Bailey will come off the bench
in his homecoming here in Chicago.

1507
01:22:33,449 --> 01:22:36,452
We have nine of the top ten prospects
in the class in this game.

1508
01:22:36,535 --> 01:22:37,995
There is Dereck Lively.

1509
01:22:38,079 --> 01:22:41,540
The ability to run the floor,
catch it and finish it. 7-1.

1510
01:22:41,624 --> 01:22:44,752
Amari Bailey in for the first time.
Chicago's own.

1511
01:22:46,003 --> 01:22:48,214
The number-two player in the ESPN 100s.

1512
01:22:48,297 --> 01:22:50,383
Bailey the lefty cans the three.

1513
01:22:50,466 --> 01:22:55,596
Cam Whitmore going sky-high
for the rejection. And Ernest Udeh.

1514
01:22:55,680 --> 01:22:58,683
Guys, listen to me. No layups.
No layups. Nothing chancing.

1515
01:22:59,266 --> 01:23:01,394
It's the best players, so, you know.

1516
01:23:01,477 --> 01:23:03,562
And I always wanted to put myself
against the best players.

1517
01:23:03,646 --> 01:23:05,189
I wanted to prove myself.

1518
01:23:05,272 --> 01:23:08,776
Every kid in your city you think that's
better than you, they wanna be there,

1519
01:23:08,859 --> 01:23:12,822
so it was, like, actually some of the
best times of my life during that time.

1520
01:23:12,905 --> 01:23:15,408
[Borzello] Whoa. Cason Wallace up top.

1521
01:23:15,491 --> 01:23:20,329
Whitmore. Watch out.
Take off. The windmill.

1522
01:23:20,413 --> 01:23:22,248
Dereck Lively II.

1523
01:23:22,331 --> 01:23:24,709
[commentator] Some of the NBA scouts
in attendance this week

1524
01:23:24,792 --> 01:23:26,585
have just fallen in love
with Dereck Lively.

1525
01:23:26,669 --> 01:23:29,130
If there's an NBA Draft tomorrow
from this group,

1526
01:23:29,213 --> 01:23:30,798
-Lively goes number one.
-Absolutely.

1527
01:23:30,881 --> 01:23:33,134
The East hitting triple digits

1528
01:23:33,217 --> 01:23:36,637
in the return of the McDonald's
All American Game.

1529
01:23:36,721 --> 01:23:42,184
Mitchell slashes one in too.
The final score 105 to 81.

1530
01:23:42,268 --> 01:23:45,688
The East victorious here in Chicago.

1531
01:23:45,771 --> 01:23:47,356
[fans cheering, chattering]

1532
01:23:52,361 --> 01:23:54,447
This is my family. I love 'em.

1533
01:23:54,530 --> 01:23:56,615
-Yeah. Yeah, baby.
-This is who I do it for.

1534
01:23:56,699 --> 01:24:00,161
This is what I do it for.
All love. For my family.

1535
01:24:00,244 --> 01:24:02,538
[fans cheering, clamoring]

1536
01:24:20,014 --> 01:24:22,224
-For the first time…
-For the first time ever…

1537
01:24:22,308 --> 01:24:24,393
…high school athletes can profit…

1538
01:24:24,477 --> 01:24:26,812
[all] Off of their name,
image and likeness.

1539
01:24:26,896 --> 01:24:27,938
You've heard about it.

1540
01:24:28,022 --> 01:24:30,941
It's forever changed the landscape
of college athletics, but get this.

1541
01:24:31,025 --> 01:24:34,528
Now the NIL is making moves
into the high school ranks.

1542
01:24:34,612 --> 01:24:37,823
[Hill] Now you have players
where they have representation.

1543
01:24:37,907 --> 01:24:40,576
They're businessmen and businesswomen.

1544
01:24:40,659 --> 01:24:43,037
They have agents.
They're soliciting deals.

1545
01:24:43,120 --> 01:24:47,541
It's all legal, it's part of the landscape
now in basketball.

1546
01:24:48,334 --> 01:24:50,002
[Borzello] Welcome to Houston, Texas.

1547
01:24:50,085 --> 01:24:54,173
Out of roughly a half million high school
basketball players in the nation,

1548
01:24:54,256 --> 01:24:59,553
24 of the best are here to showcase
their skills at Delmar Fieldhouse.

1549
01:25:01,639 --> 01:25:05,059
[Josiah] The whole basketball landscape
has shifted so much with social media.

1550
01:25:05,976 --> 01:25:09,772
Back in the day, these were just names
